1. # **Abstract** {#abstract}

This dissertation explores methods to integrate social science research methodology with the state-of-the-art machine learning technique, the neural networks (NNs). Chapter 1 provides a generic overview and defines the scope. Chapter 2 introduces an important working example, the College Major Preference Assessment (CMPA) and neural networks.  
Study-1, in Chapter 3, trained three multilabel neural networks (MNNs) to score the shortened version of the CMPA, introduced in Chapter 2, with preselected items by its development team for three different purposes – accuracy, recall and precision in prediction. Based on a self-developed genetic algorithm for hyperparameter tuning, the results demonstrate the effectiveness of MNNs over the traditional simple sum scoring method on the same data (at .91 accuracy, .64 recall and .34 precision). By comparison, the MNN trained for accuracy had an accuracy of .94, the one for recall had .93 recall, and for precision, .60 precision. The metrics, recall and precision, had been corrected to exclude chance guessing.  
Study-2, in Chapter 4, combined an adapted version of perturbation-based explainable AI method with Pratt’s measures, a traditional statistical powerhouse, to visualize the relative importance of trained MNNs with. The method retrains and evaluates the performance of the MNNs many times, e.g., 5000, each time with a randomly selected subset with a constant size, e.g., 50%, of the input variables. Then, the relative importance of each input variable is inferred by calculating the Pratt’s measures for a linear regression where the independent variables are the selected/disabled statuses of the input variables, and the dependent variable is the MNN’s performance outcomes. The results are obtained with the working examples of two MNNs, one trained to maximize the accuracy of CMPA short-form scoring, and the other for adjusted recall. The visualized patterns of Pratt’s were shown diagnostic of the strength of validity evidence behind the MNNs’ prediction behaviour for each college majors assessed by CMPA.  
Chapter 5 discusses the unique contributions in the context of existing pioneering fields integrating machine learning with social science research, such as psychoinformatics, computational psychometrics and educational data mining, as well as addresses the limitations and future research possibilities.

2. # **Lay Summary** {#lay-summary}

Machine learning is when computers learn to make predictions and statistics is a large part of quantitative social science research. This dissertation is an attempt to integrate both to solve psychometric problems. Chapter 1 is a generic overview and organization of the topics of the dissertation. Chapter 2 introduces the important data source, the College Major Preference Assessment (CMPA), which helps people identify what college majors they might like. It also explains the same Artificial Intelligence (AI) family as in AlphaGo or Google Translation, namely the Neural Networks (NNs), to researchers in social science, like psychology and education.   
Study-1, in Chapter 3, shows that it is possible to use the NN to make smart guesses about what the results of the full test would have been like, with only part of the test. The quality of guesses can be gauged differently for different purposes, i.e., by how close they were to the original results overall, by how good they are at catching all positive cases, or by how good they are at avoiding false alarms. Study-1 also shows that NN is so smart and flexible that it can be taught to fit different criteria better than simple sum as the baseline comparison point.  
Sometimes the AI cheats. In one of the worst cases, an AI could be denying credit card applications based on race. Study-2, in Chapter 4, provides a way to diagnose whether the AI is making smart guesses based on information it should be using. It combines a method in statistics called the Pratt’s measures, and some techniques in AI-related fields to visualize 2 AIs (of the type NN). The result shows that the method could clearly visualize areas where the AI might have just been blindly guessing and areas where they were making judgements based on information, we expected them to. This helps the researcher evaluate and improve the AI.  
Chapter 5 discusses the findings in the context of other fields that do similar things and highlight the fact that the unique contributions are to methods social scientists can use in the future.

1. ## **Introduction** {#introduction}

In recent years, computers have gotten smarter, knowing how to play chess, predict credit card frauds, analyze, and respond to human language, etc. Such intelligent behaviour is propelled by machine learning. Indeed, machine learning is a specific way of programming such that the product knows how to run statistics and take advantage of the input information to form the basis of intelligent behaviour. Machine learning bears some resemblance with quantitative methods in social science, which is its statistical core.  
However, with forerunners in fields like psychoinformatics, computational psychometrics and educational data mining, the connection between the two fields remains under-utilized. It may be attributed to the differences in how statistics in the two fields is used. Machine learning techniques have widely been applied to, and thus specialized in, solving practical problems. On the other hand, statistical techniques in social science have mainly been used to elucidate on theory and have focused on explicability. Furthermore, the nomenclatures and conventions differ, creating even more barriers for anyone interested in mixing and matching their techniques.   
Both machine learning and statistics in social science research have their strengths and limitations. The mixing and matching could be beneficial to both fields. On the one hand, machine learning can yield decisions that are the most accurate, but not comprehensible, which has dangerous implications such as denying a person’s credit card renewal based on race, exacerbating racism. This is where statistics in social science research can fill in, to diagnose and explain the decision process. On the other hand, statistics in social science research is often willing to accept a theory based on a statistical model that only predicts 30% of the cases correctly if it is statistically significant, providing weak empirical evidence. This can be strengthened by borrowing some techniques from machine learning to optimize the performance of the model with. Unfortunately, there is often a tension between optimizing explainability and prediction performance.   
This dissertation presents such a case as shows the power of mixing and matching of techniques from these two fields – yielding explainable yet high-quality predictions. More specifically, this research was motivated by a need to score a shortened version of an assessment, the College Major Preference Assessment (CMPA).  
CMPA was a practical invention developed to help prospective students identify college majors they prefer. It assesses individuals’ preference over 50 college majors that are common across North America. The final report, in principle, needs to include 50 scores, one for each major, so that the respondents’ preferences can be ranked.  
There are some challenges in scoring the 50 majors where traditional psychometrics may fall short, as we will see in Chapter 3\. First, the number of majors to score is large and the traditional parametric models would find it hard to handle such high-dimensional response data (50 categories). Second, the traditional scoring methods, like simple sum or latent scores from item response theory, can not be adapted to different score use purposes. For example, the individuals may be keener on finding out *any* majors that they might prefer and do not mind the false positives. Other times, it may be more important to find out *only* the majors they surely prefer and are willing to accept false negatives. The machine learning technique, the neural network, grants the ability to handle these challenges.  
Hence, the first study, in Chapter 3, was motivated by finding a method that can tackle the challenges of scoring the very high-dimensional assessment data and accommodate different use purposes. To do so, I borrowed from machine learning the technique called multilabel neural network (MNN). In the broader context, Chapter 3 is about how machine learning can help address psychometric issues common in social science.  
However, the multilabel neural network, being a much more complicated model than most statistical models in social science, is infamously hard to interpret. Though machine learning has made attempts to interpret neural networks, jointly forming a subfield/movement called “explainable AI,” the existing methods are not necessarily suitable for psychometric use. In my case, I wanted to diagnose if the multilabel neural network operates in a sensible way when being used as a scoring machine. This is the kind of explainability and interpretability that social science research usually focuses on. This need motivated my second study in Chapter 4 where I show how the NN is complemented by a statistical tool, Pratt’s measures, which are used in academic research to order the importance of independent variables in a regression model. Specifically, Chapter 4 describes how I adapted an intervention-based method of the explainable AI, called perturbation, and integrated it with Pratt’s measures to examine the behaviour of the multilabel neural network. Situated in the broader context, therefore, Chapter 4 completes the remaining part of the major theme in the dissertation, that statistics applied in social science research can be used to enhance machine learning methods, too.

1. ### **The Objective and Scope of This Dissertation**  {#the-objective-and-scope-of-this-dissertation}

Briefly, this dissertation answers the following research questions:  
**Question-1**: How do we score the short version of CMPA, so it works as well as the original version while accommodating different score use purposes?  
**Question-2**: How do we diagnose a neural network used for a specific purpose as stated in Question-1?  
The solution to Question-1 is multilabel neural networks, applied to optimizing different performance metrics, which I will demonstrate in Chapter 3\. The solution to Question-2 is the combination of perturbation-based intervention and Pratt’s measures, which I will demonstrate in Chapter 4\.  
Now, it is important to define the scope of this dissertation and clarify what it intends and does not intend to be: 

1. This is not a substantive study of college major preferences or career theory. Instead, this is methodological research that seeks to learn from both worlds of machine learning and statistics used in social science research – handling complex prediction problems well and being able to diagnose the prediction mechanism. CMPA is only a motivating case, not the main character.  
2. This is not a validation study of the CMPA. Instead, it is premised upon CMPA’s interpretations and use being valid.  
3. This is not a machine learning paper trying to develop a new variant of neural network. Instead, it applies what is there in ways that would make sense for social science researchers and potentially introducing the neural network into their toolkit, particularly, how the neural network contributes to flexible scoring.

Since this is not a substantive research paper or validation study, I will not report existing findings on the reliability or validity of CMPA. Since this is not a machine learning paper, I will not follow publication convention in machine learning to prove my final MNN is superior to the best existing model of its kind. This is a methodological paper written mostly for social science researchers in its essence, with a pronounced but non-dominating flavour of machine learning. Study-2 can also entertain an audience from machine learning, who will be introduced to the convenience of Pratt’s measures, a traditional statistical powerhouse. At a higher level, it is hoped that this work inspires more true interdisciplinary understanding and collaborations.  
This dissertation centers around the integration between machine learning and statistics applied in social science. I adopt slightly more generic terms in the dissertation because some of the comments and contributions made to the fields may generalize. However, it is important to clarify the meaning of the following terms I use throughout this dissertation:  
**Machine Learning:** I am specifically referring to *supervised* machine learning that deals with prediction problems, such as neural networks, decision trees, random forests, linear regression, support vector machine, etc. I mostly am not thinking about unsupervised techniques such as clustering like K-means, K nearest neighbours, reinforcement learning like Q-Matrix or policy learning, transfer learning, or semi-supervised learning.  
**Social Science:** I mostly speak of psychology, education, and psychometric research as the representatives of social science. I am admittedly less familiar with business and econometrics, which may have different conventions from psychometrics in running statistics.   
**Traditional Statistical Method:** When I refer to the traditional statistical methods or statistics applied in social science, I mostly refer to methods that are comparable to supervised machine learning, including linear regression, logistic regression, structural equation modelling (including factor analysis), principal component analysis, item response theory, linear mixed effects models (including multilevel modelling or hierarchical linear models), etc. and the Bayesian versions of them. I am not referring to latent class analysis, latent profile analysis or k-means cluster analysis that are seen as unsupervised techniques in machine learning.

2. ### **The Organization of This Dissertation** {#the-organization-of-this-dissertation}

Given the scope and foci, this dissertation starts with a slow-paced introduction in Chapter 2 to the major components involved: (1) the College Major Preference Assessment, (2) the neural network, including some specialized steps jointly called hyperparameter tuning and K-fold cross validation, and (3) perturbation-based methods and Pratt’s measures. Chapter 2 provides the most detail on CMPA to help understand the context in which the dissertation is situated but leaves the technical detail of the neural network and perturbation-based methods and Pratt’s measures to Chapter 3 and Chapter 4\. Nevertheless, Chapter 2 introduces neural networks with sufficient conceptual completeness needed for understanding the motivation and purpose of this dissertation.   
Chapter 3 is a stand-alone manuscript for Study-1 answering research Question-1: How do we score the short-version of CMPA, so it works as well as the original version while accommodating different score use purposes? It follows the typical structure of an APA research paper: Introduction, Method, Results and Discussion. The characteristics of the CMPA data will be presented in this Chapter. Different performance metrics (accuracy, precision, recall, etc.) for different score use purposes will be discussed. There is more information on the implementation detail of neural networks, including the gist of the hyperparameter tuning process. The results of using a multilabel neural network to score the short-version CMPA will be compared to using the simple sum method.  
By a similar token, Chapter 4 is a stand-alone manuscript for Study-2, focusing on answering Question-2: How do we diagnose a neural network used for a specific purpose as stated in Question-1? Like Chapter 3, it follows the structure of an APA research paper: Introduction, Method, Results and Discussion. This chapter is intended for readers who have foundational knowledge for neural networks, hence the focus will be on explainable AI and introducing my proposed method – combing perturbation-based interventions with Pratt’s measures. The report will highlight how the proposed method helps to diagnose whether the neural networks do their jobs properly as a scoring machine.  
Finally, Chapter 5 summarizes the main points of the two studies and highlights their unique contributions, mostly in terms of how re-framing research inquiries, as I did in the two studies, helps find, combine, and integrate solutions that are already available in other fields. There is also a dedicated section about the seminal work of pioneers in psychoinformatics, computational psychometrics and educational data mining, who also devoted their efforts to better integrating social science with computer science, AI, machine learning, and data science. Possible future studies extending upon the current dissertation and additional implications for machine learning will be addressed in Chapter 5, too.  
The non-essential technical detail, which would otherwise permit replicability, will be provided in the appendix. Even more fine-grained detail on the programming code can be found on my GitHub repository: [https://github.com/husohome/career\_ml](https://github.com/husohome/career_ml). 

2. ## **Background, Literature, and Methodological Foundation**  {#background,-literature,-and-methodological-foundation}

This chapter provides the background, context, and methodological foundation needed to understand the two studies in the present dissertation. In reminder, Study-1, in Chapter 3, proposed to use neural networks as a method to resolve challenges in scoring complex psychological assessments. Study-2, in Chapter 4, proposed a method to diagnose whether a trained neural network did what it was supposed to do as a scoring method with.  
As the working example for both studies, College Major Preference Assessment (CMPA) will be first introduced. Next, neural network, specifically multilabel neural network, and its essential auxiliary devices will be addressed so that the readers can understand why and how it could solve the scoring problem in Study-1. Then, I will move on to give a brief introduction to the methods for explainable artificial intelligence and justify the need for my own method for diagnosing a trained neural network, which will be showcased in Study-2.

1. ### **College Major Preference Assessment**  {#college-major-preference-assessment}

   1. #### **Context for College Major Preference Assessment** 

Choosing a college major is consequential for one’s professional life (Beggs et al., 2008). Congruence in personal interest and college major was found to positively predict learning motivation, engagement (Leuwerke et al., 2004), and academic performance, as well as college and life-long success (Willcoxson & Wynder, 2010). On the contrary, incongruence between interest and college major has resulted in overskilling (Green & Zhu, 2010), overqualification (about 20% working adults between age 25 and 49 are overqualified; Statistics Canada, 2020), underpayment (Robst, 2007; Mavromaras et al., 2012), and low job satisfaction (Mavromaras et al., 2012; Green & Zhu, 2010).  
	However, instead of directly asking if students are interested in a major, previous efforts have used items to measure a few constructs first, which are then mapped to career paths. For example, respondents might be asked to indicate their degree of enjoyment in “managing a department within a large company” or “assembling electronic parts”, which are then mapped to two of the six constructs, “Enterprising” and “Realistic” in the Holland code, often known as the RIASEC hexagon (acronym for the six constructs Realistic, Investigative, Artistic, Social, Enterprising, and Conventional; RIASEC test., n.d.; Holland, 1994). Respondents who score high on “Enterprising,” according to the test, may be suitable for a range of careers, such as bankers and business managers, and those who score high on “Realistic” may be a good fit for technicians and architects. In RIASEC, the scoring is done according to the theorized relationships among the items and career personality types, preferred job environment and career fit, which makes it a theory-based instrument.  
Such theory-based instruments, nonetheless, have mostly been developed for career interests and career personality types (e.g., Strong-Campbell Interest Inventory, Strong & Campbell, 1971; or the Minnesota Interest Blank, Johnson et al., 1975), which are not exactly assessing interests in “college majors”. The closest in the literature is the CAPA[^1] system by Betz and Borgen (2010) which maps college majors to “interest groups”, but, like how the RIASEC abstracts away from specific occupations using theoretical constructs, it also involves a high level of abstraction. There is a lack of instruments for direct assessment of college major preference. The College Major Preference Assessment (iKoda, 2017\) was developed with an aim to fill this gap.

2. #### **What is CMPA and Where the Content Comes from?**

Designed with practical use in mind, CMPA assists the users in identifying the college majors of their preference directly. This assessment helps the users process the key information about 50 majors. It uses Likert-type and forced-choice items along with other screening criteria to help narrow down on the preferred options (Wu, 2021). The results can be used to compare the strengths of preferences for different majors for the same, but not different individuals. The target users are anyone who wants to find their preferred majors, including prospective college students or even 2nd or 3rd year college students who are at the point of determining a major to complete their degree with.  
The CMPA assesses preferences for college majors using items with content extracted through text mining. The text data were the descriptions of the programs and mandatory courses on the websites of forty Northern American universities and colleges. The item content was created based on the extracted key phrases that represented the nature, activities, work, topics, and skills covered by the majors. For example, one such key phrase for Geology is “how earthquakes occur,” and for Psychology is “how the mind controls behaviour,” and for Material Sciences is “how plastic reacts when stressed.”   
	Key phrase identification is done using the Term-Frequency-Inverse-Document-Frequency (TF-IDF) index (Ramos, 2003). The program/course descriptions (“documents”) in their raw forms are first classified by the majors they belong to. Then, a quantity called *TF-IDF=* TF×ln1DF is computed for every word in the documents. The TF-IDF is the product of the frequency of the term (word) and the inverse of number of documents for the different majors in which the term appears. The TF-IDF assigns large values to words that appear frequently and appear frequently only in the contexts of certain majors. This helps identify the most discriminating phrases amongst the majors. For each major, the ten phrases that contain the highest TF-IDF are selected as the key phrases, and the language is simplified to grade-10 level. Thus, the CMPA content is grounded in reality, in the sense that the assessment contents are authentic and specific, taken from real college websites describing what students really must learn.   
The CMPA demo version I recreated is available at [https://dry-retreat-23166.herokuapp.com/](https://dry-retreat-23166.herokuapp.com/). It does not store any user data.

3. #### **The Format and Procedure of CMPA**

   1. ##### **Stage-1: Likert-type Questions**

The CMPA has two stages. Stage-1 consists of three rounds of Likert-type questions. In each round, the items ask the respondents about their degree of preference for 33 majors.   
Stage-1 has three rounds of 33 items, hence a total of 99 items. Each major is assessed once in each round. Each round uses a different item for each major. As in , the question is stated as: “I want to learn about Phrase A.” where the Phrase A is a key phrase extracted by TF-IDF for major A. The respondents provide their answer on a 4-point Liker scale of Strongly Disagree, Disagree, Agree, and Strongly Agree that are scored as 0, 1, 2, and 3, respectively.  displays the layout of a Likert-type item for Education as an example.   
**Figure 2.1** *Examples of Likert and Forced-choice Items in CMPA*

After these three Likert rounds, a person has 33 sum scores, each ranging from 0 to 9, for each of the 33 majors. These 33 sum scores then are used to screen in majors that a respondent prefers. Specifically, a major is screened in for a respondent if its sum score is higher than the mean across all majors for that respondent.   
Figure **2.2** shows Stage-1 procedure with Sarah’s responses to only three majors for explanation. Given her answers, by the end of Stage-1, she would have accumulated 6 points for Psychology, 5 points for General Business, and 1 point for Computer Science. Her personal mean across the three rounds would be (6 \+ 5 \+ 1\) / 3 \= 4\. That is, only the majors with a sum score above 4 would be screened in for Stage-2 assessment. In Sarah’s case, they are Psychology and General Business.

2. ##### **Stage-2: Forced-choice Questions**

The format of Stage-2 is pairwise forced choice. Each item asks the respondents to choose from two options. All the items are presented as “I would rather spend time learning Phrase A or Phrase B,” where Phrase A and Phrase B are key phrases for major A and B. The two majors must have both been screened in by Stage-1. See Figure 2.1 for an example forced-choice item for Education vs. Psychology.  
There are four rounds of forced-choice questions. The procedure for the first three rounds is the same but repeated with different key phrases. That is, the majors screened in are randomly paired without replacement to create items. The top three (could be more than three if there are ties) most frequently chosen majors across these three rounds then enter the fourth (final) force-choice round where all top three (with ties) are compared in a pairwise manner.  
The inclusion of the two-stage assessment format and the screening devices make the assessment increasingly personalized to reflect one’s preference. After completing the assessment, the respondent receives a profile for the majors screened in by Stage-1, ranked by their scores from Stage-2, which are the number of times the respondent chooses the major. For the detail of the two-staged procedure, please see Wu (2021).  
Note that the possible range of the score for each major in Stage-2 will vary across respondents, depending on how many majors and whether general majors are screened in and unpacked for Stage-2, and whether there are ties at the end of round six. Thus, the CMPA scores should not be used to compare across individuals; rather, the scores should be used to rank a person’s preference over the majors.
