4. #### **The Validity of CMPA**

The main idea of CMPA is *preference*. It is operationally defined as the number of times a respondent chooses the phrase of a major against another. To be clear, only responses to Stage-2 are counted. Stage-1 is simply there to screen in majors. Thus, preference is distinguished from interest (as in Strong-Campbell Interest Inventory for example, Strong & Campbell, 1971\) in a few important ways. While interest is conceptualized as a construct that manifests itself in career choices, preference is the choice itself. This choice is grounded in reality, such that the phrases in the items are directly taken from authentic program websites and course descriptions about what one will have to learn specifically. CMPA makes no claim that this choice taps into the construct of interest, as the choice can be driven by other factors such as conformity (e.g., Gabrielsen, 1992), money (e.g., Ma, 2009; Han & Winters, 2020), “my parents said so” (e.g., Ma, 2009), but of course, by interest, too (Päßler & Hell, 2012). That is, interest could be one, but not the only, reason for preference. Likewise, the CMPA makes no claim about the stability of such preferences over time.  
According to the CMPA development team, preference is strictly personal and cannot be used for consequential decisions by others such as college admission. This is because (1) respondents’ final scores are on slightly different scales, (2) the number of items administered to the respondents varies, and (3) the screening mechanisms are based on personal means, not group means (See Table 2.2 for more explanations and detail). Last but not least, CMPA does not claim that choosing a major one prefers means the person necessarily fits in, does well in, or will not change thoughts about the major.  
A quick summary of the intended interpretation and use of the CMPA scores is provided below:  
1\. CMPA scores simply tell us what the preferences are at the time the scores are yielded and no more. The scores cannot be directly interpreted as interest, or any reasons why the preferences arise, or how stable the preferences are, or how good a fit a person would be for the major.  
2\. CMPA scores are strictly within-person. The comparison of one’s scores to those of another is meaningless, or at least, not the intended way in which CMPA scores are used. The scores are on different scales.  
3\. CMPA scores are for personal reference and cannot be used in highly consequential scenarios.  
Today, it is a consensus that validity is not a property of the test, but of a claim, a claim that the test results can be interpreted and used in the way the test proposes to (e.g., Kane, 2013; Standards, 2014). The interpretation and use put forth by the CMPA are straightforward, that the scores are preference for the major, or the choice itself, for low-risk, personal references only. Since preference is strictly the number of times the respondent chooses a major, the CMPA interpretation and use are argued to be valid as no further interpretation than the fact that the respondent chose more of the topics in a major than other majors is proposed. Further, the item content is grounded in reality. Thus, based on Kane’s argument-based approach (Kane, 2013), the above reasoning should suffice as at least preliminary validation for the interpretation and use of the CMPA. In addition, by way of a latent trait model, Mao et al. (2022) and Wu (2021) showed that both Likert and forced-choice assessments served to fulfill that for which they are designed. With the findings in support of the assumptions and warrants for the validity argument, she demonstrated that CMPA works effectively for its intended interpretation and use. For more concrete validation reports, thorough consideration of the interpretation and use, and latent trait model specifications, please refer to Wu (2021).

5. #### **Short Version of CMPA**

With all the items and assessment rounds, a respondent could spend up to 40 minutes to complete the two-stage, seven-round procedure. Deeming this to be acceptable but not ideal, the development team thus considered a short-version CMPA, which only includes the Likert-type items of Stage-1. This was to save respondents’ time to answer the force-choice items. Also, Likert-type items are easier to answer, and most respondents are accustomed to them. As normally would be done for scoring a short version, the development team’s original scoring method is to use the sum score over the three corresponding Likert items to represent individuals’ preference for a major. What this means is illustrated in   
Figure **2.2**. Sarah’s answers up to the end of Stage-1 gave Psychology 6 points, General Business 5, and Computer Science 1\. Suppose if there had only been three majors assessed, the short version of CMPA would then tell the respondent, Psychology was the best preferred, General Business ranked 2nd, and Computer Science ranked the last. In brief, the original plan proposed by the development team of a short version was to just use Stage-1 and simply sum the item scores and rank the sum scores by major as in Figure **2.2**.  
Note that I was not involved in the decision about how to shorten CMPA. This is a scenario a psychometrician often faces, where the short-version items have been decided and there is no room for change. Fortunately, an extra layer of control might be granted if there is way to innovate the often-ignored scoring mechanisms, i.e., What can be improved *after* the short-form is determined?  
To my knowledge, it has been a default that in practice, after the short-form items have been selected, one simply calculates the means and/or sums of the item scores to form the dimension (subscale) or total (scale) scores. This is often the case regardless of whether the short form items were selected based on factor analysis (e.g., Donnellan et al., 2006; Raes et al., 2011; Rammstedt & John, 2007), item response theory (e.g., Paap et al., 2011\) or expert judgement (e.g., Mason et al., 2005).   
Although not the case for the short version of CMPA, the sum scores of a short form do not always correlate with, or predict, the sum score of the original form with satisfaction (e.g., Kruyen et al., 2013; Smith et al., 2000). Hence, as the main purpose of Study-1, I explore the possibility of doing more to the selected items with neural networks (NNs).  
Chapter 3 will show that using NNs to score the short version will improve the scoring performance from the simple sum method. Also, NNs can be used to score for different test uses. For example, one can choose to maximize sensitivity (a.k.a., *recall*, introduced later) as opposed to the overall accuracy, if the use purpose is to identify all the majors that are true preference at the risk of high false alarms.  
In Study-1, CMPA was presented as a motivating example where the problem of scoring assessment responses would be difficult if we were to use existing psychometric models such as item response theory and factor analysis because there would be many outcomes (majors) to score at once. The proposed solution is to reframe this problem as a prediction one and use neural networks, which do prediction well, even when the number of outcomes is large. Specifically, the predictors are the 99 Likert-type items in the CMPA short version, and the predicted variables are “whether each of the 50 majors is in a person’s top three” as determined in the original CMPA procedure. As such, the next section introduces neural networks and explains the key elements needed for the two studies in the dissertation. 

2. ### **Neural Networks** {#neural-networks}

As I will detail, Chapter 3 examines the use of neural network as a method for scoring the short version of CMPA, which includes only the Stage-1 99 Likert items, with the goal to achieve as high level of effectiveness as the full original version. The reasons for considering NN is that the traditional psychometric models, like item response theory and factor analysis do not handle prediction problems with many outcome categories well, as in the case with CMPA (50 majors). For this reason, I seek inspirations from machine learning, which has been developed, in large part, to deal with complicated prediction problems.  
In simple terms, machine learning is about making computers run numerical analysis and make decisions. Thus, like psychometrics, it has many subfields featuring different applications and choices of statistical methods. Of the ramifications, neural networks have seen the most success in recent years – giving rise to AlphaGo, AlphaStar and Google Translation, etc. Therefore, the current dissertation uses a variant of the neural network family, the multilabel neural network for the CMPA prediction problem in Study-1.

1. #### **Major Differences between Machine Learning and Traditional Statistics for Social Science Research**

As the main method in this dissertation is inspired by machine learning, it is worth understanding it from the perspective of a quantitative researcher in social science (e.g., psychology and education). Though it has been a rising trend for social science researchers to take advantage of machine learning (e.g., Montag et al., 2016; Romero et al., 2010; von Davier, Mislevy, et al., 2021), most research in such fields still uses non-machine-learning based statistical techniques. While both fields run statistics, machine learning does not emphasize *knowing* as much as statistics applied in social science research.  
To study students’ academic achievements, for example, an education researcher may ask “How do demographic variables, personality factors, and teaching methods contribute to students’ achievements?” To answer this question, the researcher might design a questionnaire, calculate the minimum sample size to reach a statistical power of .80, and collect the sample, say, of 500 students. Then, they may run a linear regression, with an emphasis on reading the regression coefficients and examine whether their *p*\-values are statistically significant, and model fit indices might be used to aid in the process. Generally speaking, traditional statistics in social science research focuses on understanding how the chosen variables are related and how the findings contribute to theory. Besides, in education and psychology, researchers are often interested in using latent variables to represent constructs (e.g., personality trait of conscientiousness) or relationships that are not directly observable.  
In contrast, machine learning rarely reasons about the variables that are not directly observable or asks questions that are theory-driven. When there is available information for 500 students, a machine learning specialist may ask “How to find an algorithm from the available information to best predicts students’ achievements?” The parameter estimates, such as regression coefficients and intercepts, are not as important as the overall prediction, indicated by metrics like the proportion of correct classifications or R-squared. Likewise, there is little emphasis on the *p*\-values, Type-I error, effect size, or statistical power. The emphasis is to find an algorithm that works the best for prediction, rather than makes theoretical sense. Given this focus, the field of machine learning has developed state-of-the-art methods for maximizing overall performance on classification and R-squared, however, with the price of producing coefficients (relationships) that are hard to interpret.  
Of machine learning methods, neural networks are often-cited for their state-of-the-art performance on practical tasks, including prediction and classification (e.g., Abu-Naser et al., 2015; Osman, 2016; Perkins et al., 1995; Stevens et al., 1999\) because they deal with non-linearity in the real-world data particularly well (e.g., Chollet, 2017; Lek et. al., 1996; Özesmi & Özesmi, 1999; Tu, 1996). Furthermore, NNs achieve so without being explicitly programmed what to do, i.e., the NN learns the rules from the data (e.g., Lau et al., 2019). There are plenty of examples of NNs excelling at education tasks. As one, Ibrahim and Rusli (2007) found NN the best at predicting the cumulative grade point average among students compared with linear regression and decision tree models. As another example, Perkins et al. (1995) could use NNs to predict the difficulty level of test items in a reading comprehension test consistently with typical psychometric method. Valko and Osadchyi (2020) proposed a framework in which NNs could maximize students’ fitness and success by helping them personalize the course of education.   
This dissertation thus intends to integrate both the advantages of NNs in prediction and traditional statistics in interpretation, as demonstrated in the two studies. Indeed, there is often a trade-off between interpretability and predictability such that the more useful the model is, the harder it is to produce explainable predictions (e.g., Linardatos, Papastefanopoulos, & Kotsiantis, 2021). On the one hand, Study-1 in Chapter 3, tries to take advantage of neural network to score the short version of CMPA to maximum overall prediction performance. On the other hand, Study-2 in Chapter 4 tries to find a method to inspect whether the neural network’s maximization of prediction makes sense, i.e., whether the prediction follows the CMPA design framework. If successful, we might benefit from having a neural network that are not only good in terms of overall performance but also interpretability.   
In the next subsection, I will introduce the neural networks from the perspective of a researcher who is familiar with linear and logistic regression and some linear algebra.

2. #### **Understanding Neural Networks with Regression and Linear Algebra**

	Neural networks are regression-like analyses (Warner & Misra, 1996). Thus, to understand them, let us take a short excursion to how regressions work.  
A typical linear regression can be expressed as this:  
Predicted = intercept + coeffecient1 Predictor1 + coefficient2 Predictor2 +  +                           coefficientP PredictorP,   
where usually both the predicted and all the predictors are available in the data set. What the linear regression does is to find the slope coefficients (weights) and intercept (baseline) and interpret them. The formula is equivalent to the common expression in linear algebra, adopted in most machine-learning-related work, to which the neural network belongs, and is given as the following:  
y = b + WTX*,*  
where *y* is a matrix containing the data for all the predicted outcomes called *labels* and X is a matrix of predictor information called *input* variables in machine learning languages. The *b* is the *bias* term, which is the machine learning language for intercept, and *W* is a matrix containing *weights* for the *P* predictors, which are the machine learning term for regression coefficients. The *WTX* is the dot product of *W* and *X*, which is the linear algebra notation for the weighted sum of predictors and coefficients, i.e., coeffecient1 Predictor1 + coefficient2 Predictor2 +  + coefficientP PredictorP. This linear-algebra notation, consistent with that in Mal'tsev (1963), will be adopted for this dissertation for its brevity.   
When the outcome is a categorical variable, the linear relationship with the predictors is formulated via a nonlinear link function. Traditional logistic regression is one such formulation with a logit link for the dichotomous outcomes. It follows that the natural log of odds (a.k.a., logit) is a linear combination of the predictors given as,   
logit= lnp(y=1|X)p(y=0|X)= b+WTX,  
which can be non-linearly transformed to the probability of outcome being positive (vs. negative) by the following formula,  
 P(y=1|X)= 11+e-b+WTX  
This non-linear transformation from logit to probability is important for understanding neural networks because it is called an *activation function* in neural network terms. The purpose of an activation function in neural network is to transform the outcomes to some measures, like a probability, that is easy to understand or work with afterwards. The *sigmoid* activation function, widely used in machine learning, is exactly the logistic function with a logit link. The following formula for sigmoid activation function, adapted[^2] from what is commonly used in the neural network literature, highlights this view:  
y=11+e-b+WTX  
where the  is denotes the activation function, which transforms the ys into probabilities by the formula on the right-hand side with logits \= b+WTX.   
In practice, the activation function could be other options of the user’s choice, depending on a number of factors. However, no matter which one is deem suitable, it will be denoted as  in the following introduction of neural network.

3. #### **The Basic Units of a Neural Network – Nodes and Layers**

The building blocks of a neural network are *nodes* (e.g., Anthony, & Bartlett, 2009; Chollet, 2017), which are linear regression results transformed by a non-linear activation function (Warner & Misra, 1996). That is, a node is y*,* which is a statistically created variable whose values are only possible after the weights and intercept are estimated. The left panel of Figure 2.3 shows a simplified example of a node (a circle) receiving three input variables. Using the previous notation, Node 1 can be written as, Node1 = σb + WTX, where  is an activation function, b + WTX is y the predicted y of a linear regression using *X \=* \[*x1, x2, x3*\] as the input predictors, *W* \= \[*w1, w2, w3*\] as the weights, and *b* as the bias (intercept).  
	The right panel of Figure 2.3 shows two other nodes Node 2 and Node 3 that are fitted simultaneously using the same three input variables and same activation function. The three nodes together form a *layer* of nodes. A layer, thus, is a collection of statistically created variables. The weights are allowed to be different for the nodes. That is, Node 2 and Node 3 can also be expressed as b + WTX*,* with different *W* and *b* but the same *X*. Note that the bias term is not drawn in the Figure 2.3 just to keep the figure simple.   
The layer on the right panel of Figure 2.3 is a *dense layer* (e.g., Géron, 2019\) where all the input variables are connected to all nodes, i.e., all weights and biases are freely estimated. Sometimes, the weights may be put on some equality constraints, hence making a layer not dense.   
**Figure 2.3** *Example Nodes in Neural Network*   
*Note**.*** Left panel: a single Node that receives input directly from observed data. Right panel: a (dense) layer of nodes that receives input from the input data; the bias term is not shown to keep the figure simple. 

Nodes may also be receiving input from other nodes as shown in Figure 2.4 where Node 4 and 5 receive input from Node 1, 2 and 3\. If we put the values of Node 1, 2 and 3 in *Z*, where *Z* is \[*Node 1, Node 2, Node 3*\], then Node 4 and 5 can each be expressed as σ'b + WTZ, where *Z* is \[b + WTX, σb'+ W''TX, σb''W''TX\]; the different numbers of primes (') in the superscripts for *b* and *W* are just to highlight the fact that they are different sets of values. Substituting *Z* for their values, Node 4 (or Node 5\) can be expressed as 'b'''WT\[σb + WTX, σb' + W'TX, σb''W''TX\]*.*   
The prime for  in  σ'b + WTZ highlights the fact that the activation function may be different for different layers. That is, compared with the raw data \[*x1, x2, x3*\], the values in Node 4 (and Node 5\) have gone through the following sequence of operations:

1. An affine transformation involving a model estimated set of weights and bias. An *affine transformation* is anything that can be written in the general form *ATX* \+ *b* (Strang, 1993).  
2. A non-linear transformation by an activation function.  
3. Another affine transformation involving another estimated set of weights and bias  
4. Another non-linear transformation by an activation function.

What a layer does is, first, an affine transformation involving an estimated set of weights and bias, and second, a non-linear transformation (activation function). Adding another layer means adding another affine transformation paired with another non-linear transformation, with the input data being nodes in the previous layer. If the activation function happens to be sigmoid, then each node in a layer is just the predicted probabilities by a logistic regression. Adding another layer that also uses the sigmoid activation function is just running another set of logistic regressions, with the predicted values by the previous logistic regressions as the input variables.  
**Figure 2.4** *The Basic Structure of a Neural Network*  
*![A picture containing text, electronicsDescription automatically generated][image2]*  
	Let us take a closer look at Figure 2.4, which shows the basic structure of a neural network. The neural network organizes all variables into layers (e.g., Agatonovic-Kustrin & Beresford, 2000). The raw data on predictors are often referred to as the *input layer*. Following the input layer is one to many *hidden layers*, which involve variables created using the combined affine-activation transformation of information from the previous layer. The number of hidden layers need is judged by the user; Figure 2.4 shows two hidden layers as an example. If there are more hidden layers, the subsequent nodes would undergo more affine-activation transformations.  
The last layer, *output layer*, works the same as the hidden layers, except the values of them are interpreted as the final outcomes. That is, if the outcome variable has multiple categories, the nodes in the output layer (Node 6, 7, and 8 in Figure 2.4) would each represent one category of the outcome variable. The fact that there are three nodes in the output layer in Figure 2.4 means there are three outcome categories. For the convenience of understanding, let us assume Nodes 6, 7, and 8 correspond to outcome category Q, R, and S, respectively. Since in the output layer, Nodes 6, 7, and 8 would have gone through the affine-activation transformation three times. That is, Node 6 can be represented as the following:  
	Node 6= p(y \= Q| X)= ''W''T'W'T WTX \+ b+b'+b''.  
If we let *V* denote the result of previous steps, which amount to 'W'T WTX \+ b+b'*, t*hen Node 6 can be rewritten as   
Node 6= p(y \= Q| X)= WTV+b.  
For Node 7 and 8, we can simply replace the left-hand side of Node 6 with p(y \=R| X) and p(y \= S| X), respectively, and know in mind that the weights, biases, and the results of the previous steps could be different from those for Node 6\.  
	To deepen understanding, let us link the neural network back to regression models. It should hopefully be clear by now that a neural network is a series of regressions, which take inputs from previous non-linear regressions. Thus, a traditional univariate ordinary linear regression can be thought of as one node that directly takes input from the raw input data with no hidden layers and no activation function applied. Likewise, a traditional logistic regression is one node, that directly takes input from the raw data, with no hidden layers, with the sigmoid activation function applied. 

4. #### **Activation Functions**

As mentioned, the sigmoid function is one commonly used activation function. The sigmoid function is the same as the nonlinear transformation from logits to probabilities in logistic regression. It transforms the linear combination of nodes in previous layers, i.e., logit \= *m*, into 11+e-m*.* The transformed quantity ranges from 0 to 1 and can be interpreted as a probability. As such, the sigmoid function is often applied for the outcome layer to produce probabilities that can then be used to classify categorical outcomes by applying a cut-off, usually 0.5 (i.e., ≤ 0.50 is negative and \> 0.5 is positive). This is how I set up the multilabel neural networks in Study-1 to be, where each of the 50 values in the output layer was the predicted probability of whether that major was in the respondents’ top three. Then each probability was classified into a binary outcome of No/Negative if probability ≤ 0.50, or Yes/Positive if probability \> 0.50.  
Other popular activation functions include hyperbolic tangent (tanh), which is e2m-1e2m+1, which transform the predicted values to fall between \-1 and 1, and Rectified Linear Unit, ReLU[^3], which is *m*,  *m \> 0, and 0  m  0*. These two activation functions are often used in the hidden layers for its computational efficiency and good performance (e.g., Chollet, 2017; Ketkar, 2017).

5. #### **Finding a Good Neural Network**

   1. ##### **Hyperparameter Tuning**

The effectiveness of a neural network is not only decided by its parameter estimation but also the hyperparameters – its configuration. Parameters are unknown quantities that relate the input and output variables. For example, the weights and biases of a neural network are parameters. The best set of parameters is found (estimated) based on the observed information in the input and outcome variables. Hyperparameters are other settings related to the neural network that can impact the performance in addition to the observed data. For example, the number of layers and number of nodes in each layer are hyperparameters. This section briefly explains what hyperparameter tuning is – an exercise to find the best configuration for a neural network.  
The neural network performance is naturally affected by the quality of the parameter estimates, but the hyperparameters could matter even more. Imagine an extreme case where the researcher sets up only one node for only one layer for the data that have 1000 input variables. Naturally, the information will be reduced too much to produce good prediction results. On the contrary, too many layers and two many nodes in each layer can make the estimation unnecessarily complex and time-consuming but make no extra gains in prediction performance. Thus, finding a good set of hyperparameters, a practice called “hyperparameter tuning,” is paramount for the effectiveness of a neural network. Of the hyperparameters for neural networks, the number of hidden layers and how many nodes for each layer, are the two most consequential hyperparameters for the effectiveness of an NN (e.g., Chollet, 2017).  
While it sometimes suffices to manually experiment on the values of these two hyperparameters to see which setup is optimal, some automatic searching strategies might be worth employing as the neural network gets more complex. The following paragraph provides a quick summary of these automatic searching strategies for the optimal set of hyperparameters.  
*Grid search* involves going through a set of reasonably pre-specified values of hyperparameters of concern. For example, the researcher may search through all the combinations of 1 to 12 as the number of layers and 20 to 200 nodes for each layer. Because there will be too many combinations (13  181 \= 2353\) to try out to see under which setting the NN will produce the best performance, an alternative strategy is *random search*, which randomly picks some of the combinations and sees which ones produces the best performance. Because random search is luck-dependent, some strategies, like *genetic algorithms* were developed to overcome this problem. Genetic algorithms first draw a number of random sets of initial hyperparameters, say 100\. Then, after the 100 sets of hyperparameters are tried out on the input data, the best performing few, say 20, that yield the best prediction, are allowed to “reproduce” children, and evolve. Reproduction means that new hyperparameter values sets will be created by inheriting from (i.e., copying) their parents’ settings. Meanwhile, the algorithms will mutate some of the randomly chosen settings for their idiosyncrasies. The same culling and reproduction cycle is repeated many times, say 50, and the researcher reaps the best performing of them all after 50 generations of evolution. Chapter 3 has a more detailed explanation on genetic algorithms.  
Surprisingly, the seemingly more informed strategies like genetic algorithms do not always outperform random search. Thus, manual trial and error, random search, or grid search all remain a common practice in hyperparameter tuning (e.g., Skinner & Riddle,.2007; Yu & Zhu, 2020). 

2. ##### **Training: Finding the Best Parameters** 

This section deals with finding the optimal set of parameters, such as weights and biases, for the neural network, given the observed data. In machine learning language, this process is also called “training” or “fitting” a model. 

1. ###### **Cross Entropy: The Loss Function**

Like fitting a regression model, training a neural network is synonymous for finding the optimal weights and biases. To do so, one needs certain criterion to evaluate whether the best-fitting set of parameters is found. In a typical ordinary linear regression, the criterion is “the sum of squared errors,” where errors are the differences between the observed and predicted values. If the sum of squared errors is large, the regression model did not do a good job because the predicted values were far off from the real data values. Thus, the best set of weights and intercepts should minimize the sum of squared errors. The function that quantifies how bad the model is, and thus ought to be minimized, is called the loss function, and the choice of it often depends on the distribution of the outcome variable, e.g., binomial, or continuous (e.g., Chollet, 2017; Janocha & Czarnecki, 2017).  
In a typical neural network that involves binary classifications, the loss function is usually binary cross entropy, which is defined as,   
BinaryCrossEntropy=-1Ni=1Nyi ∙lnpi+1 \- yi∙ln1- pi  
where yi is the binary label of the outcome variable, which is 1 if the outcome is positive and 0 if the outcome is negative. In the case of Study-1, the positive outcome would be “Yes, the major is in the respondent’s top three.” and the negative outcome would be “No, the major is not in the respondent’s top three.” The pi is the predicted probability of outcome is Yes by the neural network. *N* is the number of observations (respondents). The negative multiplier in the beginning of the right-hand side of the equation is to make sure a larger entropy value would mean poorer fit to the data so that it is a “loss” function. The binary cross entropy punishes deviations from correct classifications (De Boer et al., 2005); hence, the best sets of weights and biases is identified by minimizing it. 

2. ###### **Five-Fold Cross Validation**

To ensure generalizability of the neural network results, it is common to follow a K-fold cross validation procedure in the training process. (Chollet, 2017; Géron, 2019). K-fold cross validation first separates the data into *K* \+ 1 equally sized parts, with one part called the *test* data, one part called the *validation* data, and the remaining parts called the *training* data. Figure 2.5 shows an illustrative case of a five-fold (*K* \= 5\) cross validation with 9442 respondents of CMPA for Study-1. This means the test data set will contain 1574 respondents, the validation data set will contain another 1574 respondents, and the training data set will contain the remaining 6294 respondents.  
**Figure 2.5** *An Illustration of Five-fold Validation with 9442 Observations*  
![DiagramDescription automatically generated][image3]  
The five-fold cross validation will be done *K* times; that is, the exercise of training-validation-testing will be conducted *K* times, each time a different part of the data is used for validation, but the same kept part is used for testing. As in Figure 2.5, for example, the first time of training uses the first 1574 rows for validating the NN results trained on the data in rows 1575 to 7866, the second time uses the data in rows 1575 to the 3146 rows for validating the data trained on rows 1 to 1575 and rows 3147 to 7866 combined, and so on, when the last time the last 1574 rows are used as the validation data.  
The train data are essentially the 6294 rows of data that are not reserved for validation or testing. This process is repeated five times, each time using a different set of 6924 rows of data in training. After each time of training, the found weights and biases are applied to the validation data, which are also different each time, and applied to the test data, which are the same across all the *K* times of training. As such, each time, two sets of performance indexes be obtained: one set reflects how well the neural network results generalize to the validation data, and the other reflects how well the results generalize to the test data that are never used in the training-validation cycle.  
The reason K-fold cross validation becomes a convention is that neural networks can be trained to fit exceedingly well to a given sample data, to an extent that trained neural network may not generalize well to new samples. The reason the cross validation is done for K times rather than the usual one-time practice in social science research is to ensure validation is not based on the fluke of one haphazard half split of the data. If the training performance indexes are similar across the K times cross-validations, then generalizability to new data is not too much of a worry. Also, averaging performance indexes over five times of cross-validations provides a more reliable evaluation of the neural network’s effectiveness. 

2. ### **Explaining a Neural Network** {#explaining-a-neural-network}

   1. #### **The Need to Explain the Neural Network**

	As a long-standing criticism against NNs is that they are not easily interpretable (e.g., Buhrmester et al., 2021; Dayhoff & DeLeo, 2001; Müller et al., 2019; Oh et al., 2019; Paliwal & Kumar, 2011; Shwartz-Ziv & Tishby, 2017; Zhang et al., 2018), intuitively defined as the understandability to human users here (see a discussion of the term *interpretability* in Miller, 2019). While it is recognized that NNs predict the outcome(s) well, it is unclear how and why. What if a neural-network-based credit card issuing decision system excluded an applicant based on race, exacerbating racism in North America (Serna et al., 2019; Zou & Schiebinger, 2018)? What if in sensitive areas like NN-based medical decisions “\[t\]he reality … reveals an inability of deep learned systems to communicate effectively with their users” (Goebel et al., 2018, p. XX)? The opacity of neural network’s prediction mechanisms makes it an unsuitable tool in academia because academic research often aims to explain, not just to predict. Furthermore, if the neural network is used to predict an outcome variable of an assessment, as in the case of scoring the short version of CMPA, the opacity would make it hard to know if the scoring is valid.  
For better interpretability and replicability (Holzinger et al., 2017), it is necessary to open the black box and inspect whether the NN behaved appropriately before its prediction is used to make important conclusions and decisions (e.g., Arrieta et al. 2020; Doran et al., 2017; Holzinger et al., 2018). Understanding how and why NNs work can also facilitate debugging, knowledge discovery, and improvements in training (Adadi & Berrada, 2018). These beliefs are embraced in the interdisciplinary movement of *Explainable Artificial Intelligence* (Explainable AI) (e.g., Samek et al., 2019). A few attempts to open the black box of a neural network reveal cases where the AI was actually reliant on hints that had nothing to do with the main task. This phenomenon is called “Clever Hans” (Lapuschkin et al., 2019), attributed to a seemingly smart horse Hans, first documented in Pfungst (1911). As in Figure 2.6, directly taken from Figure 2a in Lapuschkin et al. (2019), the AI was trained to classify pictures of horses vs. non-horses (the main task). However, it was trained on a data set in which all photos of horses happened to have a watermark to the bottom left. Thus, the AI, seemingly able to do a good job telling horses from non-horses, did so only taking the information of the watermark (unrelated to the main task – judging whether there is an image of horse in the photo). The right panel of Figure 2.6 shows a heatmap where reddish colours indicate that the pixels in the photo that the AI relied heavily on to make predictions. The redder the colour, the more reliant the neural network relies on the parts of the image. If the AI were learning to identify horses, it should at least refer to pixels that constitute part of the horse.  
**Figure 2.6** *An* *Example of the Clever Hans Phenomenon Taken from Lapuschkin et al. (2019)*  
![MapDescription automatically generated][image4]*Note.* This picture is taken from Lapuschkin et al. (2019)’s Figure 2a, which shows how Explainable AI visualizes the AI behaviour.  
The Clever Hans phenomenon shows that good prediction performance alone is not enough. Methods to open the black box and understand what the AI does are needed, which motivates my Study-2.

2. #### **Existing Explainable AI Methods**

There exist three main families of methods for explainable AI. The first is intervention-based methods of perturbation and sensitivity-analysis. These methods selectively change (manipulate) some parts of the input, and see how prediction performance are affected (e.g., Jahandideh-Tehrani, 2020; Lek et al., 1996a; Lek et al., 1996b; Park, 2007; Scardi & Harding, 1999; Schleiter, 1999; Zeiler & Fergus, 2014). Second, the functions, derivatives and other math-based methods deal with the mathematical underpinnings of the machine learning training process (i.e., gradient descent, e.g., Dimopoulos, 1999; Simonyan & Zisserman, 2014). Third, the ensemble methods are based on data re-sampling, subsetting the data several times and explaining them locally to then put the local explanations together again to evaluate the full picture (e.g., Ribeiro et al., 2016). Fourth, the structure-based methods look at the internal structure of the neural network to explain it (Binder et al., 2016; Montavon et al., 2017).  
These existing methods for explainable AI are sometimes used in companionship with auxiliary visualization techniques such as neural interpretation diagrams (Özesmi & Özesmi, 1999). Specifically, for NNs for computer vision, visual bag of words, and related methods are ways to cluster parts of the image to identify meaningful units such as the pixels representing the beak of a bird in an image (e.g., Filliat, 2007). There is also textualization techniques, which attempt to describe the judgements by the AI systems in text.  
	Most of these methods have primarily found their root in the field of Computer Vision (e.g., Figure 2.6), or when the computer is trained to classify images. Though the means diversify, they visualize the parts in the image that each layer in a neural network is capturing and use such information to evaluate the neural network (e.g., the heat map in the right panel of Figure 2.6). For example, if a neural network can label an image as a horse, we would know that the neural network is functioning properly if some nodes are reacting to the part of the image that belongs to the horse (e.g., hooves and/or face). On the contrary, it would raise issues if all the nodes are reacting to what looks complete noise or the background like the watermark in Figure 2.6. Note that, although the techniques may differ, the basic logic behind these past methods of explainable AI is similar, i.e., to interpret the relative contributions of input variables (e.g., Angelov et al., 2021; Müller et al., 2019; Samek et al., 2017; Scardi & Harding, 1999; Sung, 1998; Vilone & Longo, 2020; Yang et al., 2022).  
Since these explanatory methods were developed from within Computer Vision, they may not be optimal for the task for this dissertation, which is not image classification. Not withstanding, the basic logic behind is still applicable, i.e., which input variables are more important. Thus, I see a room for the long-existing method for input variable importance, Pratt’s measures, to provide more intuitive visualization. For these reasons, Study-2 aims to propose a new method, taking advantage of the combined strengths of intervention-based perturbation method in explainable AI and a method for ordering predictor importance for regression in academic research (Pratt, 1987; Thomas et al.,1998; Wu et al., 2014; Wu & Zumbo, 2017).

3. #### **Combining Perturbation Intervention and Ordering Predictors Importance**

Using the trained neural network like in Study-1 as a working example, I will demonstrate how the combined method can help unpack the neural network by examining whether the prediction makes good sense, i.e., whether the prediction follows the design of CMPA. That is, for Study-2, I want to know, when using neural network to score the short-version CMPA, whether the items that are designed to assess preference for a specific major (of the 50), say Psychology, are indeed the more important input variables for predicting whether Psychology is in respondent’s top three.  
The motivation for combining the two methods is this: The perturbation-based method, among many other explainable AI, is the most intuitive method and easiest to implement on modern computers, permitting replicability. Unfortunately, as we will show in Study-2, the traditional perturbation methods do not always give easily identifiable or sensible pattern for evaluating the relative importance of the input variables. This gap is exactly where Pratt’s measure can fill in. The detail of the combined method will be explained in Chapter 4\.

3. ### **Summary** {#summary}

This chapter introduced the College Majors Preference Assessment, neural networks, and explanatory artificial intelligence to provide the foundation and context for understanding the two studies in this dissertation.   
CMPA was presented as a motivating example where the problem of scoring the assessment responses is difficult because there are many outcomes (majors) to score at once. The proposed solution here is to reframe the scoring problems as a prediction task so that one can take advantage of neural networks. Specifically, given that there are 50 outcome categories, the multilabel NN will be used to tackle the problem. The introduced concepts and procedures of multilabel NN will be realized with the CMPA working example in Study-1.  
In addition to setting up the stage for understanding neural network as a scoring method for complex psychological assessment, this chapter also discussed the need for unpacking machine learning for interpretability, especially when being used in academic settings. I briefly introduced my proposed method for explaining a neural network a method that combines perturbation-based interventions and Pratt’s measures. The rationales, steps, and benefits of the proposed method will be detailed in Chapter 4 with the example of diagnosing neural networks like the one trained in Study-1. 

3. ## **Neural Network as a Flexible Scoring Mechanism for Short Test Forms: An Example with College Major Preference Assessment** {#neural-network-as-a-flexible-scoring-mechanism-for-short-test-forms:-an-example-with-college-major-preference-assessment}

This chapter is written as a stand-alone manuscript for submission to a peer-reviewed journal. Some of the content may be the same as in Chapter 1 and 2 of this dissertation.  
This article demonstrates how a Neural Network (NN) can help solve the practical psychometric problem of scoring. It showcases how NNs can be used as a scoring machine for a short version of a psychological test to perform as effectively as the original version. In addition, the demonstration will illustrate the advantages of using NNs to score for different uses of the test. 

1. ### **Background** {#background}

This paper proposes to use neural networks to score a short-form test where the items are selected from the original test. We use the short version of College Major Preference Assessment (CMPA) as the case study for demonstration. A demo of the full version of CMPA, which does not store user data or responses, is available online ([https://dry-retreat-23166.herokuapp.com/](https://dry-retreat-23166.herokuapp.com/)).

1. #### **Creating and Scoring a Short Test Form**

It has been a common practice in many areas to develop short test forms to save testing time (e.g., Burisch, 1997; Shrout & Yager, 1989; Stanton et al., 2002), screen potential candidates medical or immigration purposes (e.g., Spitzer et al., 2006; Yesavage et al., 1982), or adapt content to a new target population (e.g., Corulla, 1990\).  
Common ways to select short form items include expert judgment (e.g., Mason et al., 2005), classical test theory (using inter-item correlations and Cronbach’s Alpha), factor analysis (using factor loadings or communalities), item-response theory (using item discrimination, item difficulty, and test information functions), and some combination of these methods (as reviewed in Coste et al., 1997; Doornenbal, 2021; Olaru et al., 2015; Smith et al., 2000), or in recent years, machine learning (e.g., Feng et al., 2020;).  
So far, academic discussions about how to develop short forms have heavily focused on the selection of the subset of items. With some scholars completely against the idea of short form (Anastasi, 1997; Levy, 1968; Nunnally, 1978), the majority who agrees to its value emphasize that the short form should match its original form as closely as possible, in the thoroughness of content coverage and the strength of validity (e.g., Coste et al., 1997; Kruyen et al., 2013; Stanton et al., 2002, p. 44). In their important work, “On the Sins of Short-Form Development,” Smith et al., (2000), for example, pointed to two of the nine specific “sins”: failing to show that the short form reproduces the factor structure of a multifactorial instrument and preserves the content domains represented by the subfactors. Though criticizing the use of short forms, the major criterion was mostly the same as those of supporting short forms – the match between the short and original forms.  
The evaluation of the match to the original form often focuses on the steps *during* short form development. For example, the evaluation often focuses on whether the selected items fully cover the original content (e.g., Kleka & Soroko, 2018; Kruyen, 2013; Smith et al., 2000). While these steps are important (e.g., Kruyen et al., 2013; Smith et al., 2000; Ziegler et al., 2014), psychometricians and researchers often do not have much control over the selection of the items and are mere users of the short forms. Fortunately, an extra layer of match might be granted if we innovate the often-ignored scoring mechanisms, i.e., what is the better way to score the short-form items *after* they have been determined?  
To our knowledge, the scoring mechanisms for the short forms remain underdeveloped – the convention in practice is simply calculating the means or sums of the item scores to obtain the dimension (sub-scale) scores or the total (scale) scores. This is the case even when the short form items were evaluated, selected, and validated using measurement models that can also be used to score them, such as factor analysis (e.g., Donnellan et al., 2006; Raes et al., 2011; Rammstedt & John, 2007;) and item response theory (e.g., Paap et al., 2011).  
As we will show later, even after the short form items are determined, there is room for improvement in scoring. With neural networks (NNs), it is not only possible to further improve the match in prediction (e.g., whether Psychology is in one’s top three), but also to optimize different criteria for different uses. For example, one can choose to maximize sensitivity (a.k.a. recall, introduced later), as opposed to the overall accuracy in prediction, if the purpose is to identify all the true positive cases, and a high false positive rate is less of a concern. This capability of scoring for different test uses will be a great addition to psychometrics.   
Before homing in on NNs, in what follows, we introduce the CMPA as the case study. The introduction provides the key information for the design and scoring of the original and short versions of CMPA, which are pivotal to understanding the current case study.

2. #### **The College Majors Preference Assessment (CMPA)**

The CMPA is the case that motivates the current research. The original version was designed to assist (prospective) college students to choose from a pool of 50 majors common in North America colleges and universities (iKoda, 2017). The assessment content is grounded in reality and authenticity such that the item content is the key phrases extracted from the online textual program/course information, describing the actual subjects, activities, and skills that the students must learn. For example, “how earthquakes occur” is one such key phrase for Geology, “how the mind controls behaviour” is for Psychology, and “how plastic reacts when stressed” is for Material Sciences.  
The original CMPA consists of seven assessment rounds, separated into two stages by two assessment formats. Stage-1 has three rounds of 33 Likert-type rating items. Each item asks how much the respondent likes to learn about a key phrase for a major. The respondents provide their answers on a 4-point scale of Strongly Disagree, Disagree, Agree, and Strongly Agree and are scored from 0 to 3, respectively. The task of Stage-1 is to narrow the majors down to a shorter list of candidates.  
Stage-2 of CMPA consists of four rounds of pairwise forced-choice items. Each item forces the respondent to choose one of the two phrases, describing nature, activities, work, topics, and skills of two majors. The major chosen gets a score of 1\. The task of Stage-2 is to further narrow the majors down to a respondent’s top three (with possible ties).   
In addition, over the two-stage assessment, some screening steps are applied to rule out some majors from further assessment (see Wu, 2021 for detail). This results in an adaptive test that is increasingly personalized to a respondent. The final report presents one’s top three majors (with ties) and their scores. The interpretation and use of the results should only be personal. i.e., it cannot be used to compare across individuals. Wu (2021) and (Mao et al. 2022\) provided validity evidence for the intended interpretation and use of CMPA results.   
It is necessary to point out that, to economize on time, Stage-1 only assesses thirty-three majors, instead of all fifty, because some of the majors are grouped into a few *general* majors. For example, the four majors, Accounting, Business, Economics, and Marketing are grouped under *General Business* in Stage-1. As a result, there are only 99 Likert items in the first stage (33 items  three rounds) rather than 150 items (50 items  3 rounds). The specific majors under a general umbrella are assessed individually *only* if their general major is screened in into Stage-2 assessment.   
As is, the CMPA original full version could take up to 40 minutes to complete if taken seriously. This assessment time is acceptable, but not ideal. Thus, the development team shortened it to include only the 99 Likert-type items in Stage-1 because respondents are more accustomed to, and thus can more easily, hence quickly answer questions. As normally would be done for scoring a short version, the current short-version CMPA simply uses the sum of the three corresponding Likert items of a major to represent individuals’ preference for that major. It has been reported that the sum scores of the short form, although easy to compute, does not always correlate with, or predict, the sum score of the original form (e.g., as reviewed by Kruyen et al., 2013; Smith et. al., 2000). Other more sophisticated scoring methods such as item response theory and factor analysis were not considered for CMPA because they, as parametric statistical models, are not best suited for an assessment that measures an extremely high number of 50 outcome categories (majors). 

3. #### **Why Using NN to Score a Short Form?**

What follows will give a brief overview of NN so that we can provide our reasons for proposing to use NN to score a short form. The technical detail of the NNs specific to the present study will be provided in the Analysis sub-section under the Method section.  
In machine learning, an NN is a circuit of layers of artificial neurons, called nodes, connected by directional edges. In Figure 3.1, the nodes that are horizontally aligned is called a layer. The first layer is the input data (the 99 Likert-type items of the short version for the current study), and the last layer is a set of nodes, each representing the predicted outcomes (50 probabilities for the 50 majors). The nodes are simply statistically created latent variables that are a function of the nodes in the previous layer.   
As exemplified in Figure 3.1, NNs can be thought of as layers of regressions, with the next layer of regressions receiving information from the preceding layer of regressions (Warner & Misra, 1996). That is, the predicted values for the nodes become the predictor values for the next layer of nodes. The edges representing the regression weights. The regression intercepts, not shown in Figure 3.1, represent the baseline values and are called *biases* in machine learning language. Before being fed to the next layer, the values of nodes are non-linearly transformed by an *activation* function (e.g., Anthony & Bartlett, 2009\) to help NNs capture the non-linearity in the relationships between the two layers (e.g., Chollet, 2017). Two of the mostly used activation functions are sigmoid and the Rectified Linear Unit (ReLU) (e.g., Chollet, 2017; Ketkar, 2017).   
**Figure 3.1** *Example NN Structure*![Diagram, schematicDescription automatically generated][image5]  
A good NN is one that has the optimal structure, function, and weights so that it can produce the best outcomes for *future* predictions. This task of finding the best solution is called *training* in machine learning language. NNs have been shown to do surprisingly good jobs on future prediction. For instance, fields like computer vision, where computers recognize pictures, have been propelled by the advances in NN. Recommender systems (e.g., as reviewed by Lu et al., 2015\) on YouTube are other examples of NN success stories.  
In the current study, if we can train the NN to recognize (predict) the top three majors identified by the full version CMPA with a higher level of accuracy than the simple sum scoring method, we, in essence, can improve the match between the short and full version. Since NNs have had much success in tackling tasks that are framed as prediction problems (e.g., LeCun et al., 2015), we also anticipate that the NN would perform better than the simple sum method in terms of identifying the top three majors if we can reasonably frame the scoring task as a prediction problem.  
With the simple sum, the three items of a major in the short version are treated as equally effective on assessing a person’s true preference for that major, which can be a naïve belief. In contrast, NN not only capitalize on the relationships among the items, but also allows all the items to contribute, with different weights, to the assessment of all 50 majors. Although the more sophisticated measurement models in conventional psychometrics, like factor analysis and item response theory, also have the capacity to assign different weights to different items, they operate on multivariate statistics and can fail to produce or produce ill-conditioned results when the number of outcome categories is large (i.e., 50 in the current case). This problem of analyzing data with high-dimensional outcomes can be handled by some variant of neural network such as multilabel neural networks, which we will introduced in more detail later.   
Foremost, unlike simple sums, NNs can be attuned to different performance goals: recall, precision, or accuracy for different test uses and purposes. When the goal is to maximize the detection of true positives, NNs can be trained to achieve a high level of *recall* (a.k.a., sensitivity, which is \[\# True Positives / \# Actual Positives in the Data\]. For example, Shu et al. (2019) used an NN to improve recall from 35% to 65% in detecting various types of computer security bugs, because their purpose is to ensure all bugs are identified so long as they exist, even if false alarms may be increased too. In contrast, when the goal is to make sure those who are tested positive are indeed positive, NN can be trained to achieve a high level of *precision* (a.k.a., positive predictive value), which is \[\#True Positives/ \# Predicted Positives\]. For example, Kaur et al. (2020) targeted a high level of precision (89%) because they did not want to diagnose a patient with Parkinson’s disease unless they were very certain, in order to avoid unnecessary panic. Of course, NNs can be trained to achieve a high level of *accuracy*, which is \[\# True Positive/ \# Total Cases\], when the goal is to ensure a high level of *overall* prediction correctness with both true positives and true negatives. For example, Han, Choi, Park, and Hong (2020) reached a 99.3% accuracy to distinguish hand-written digits from images.  
In the case of testing and assessment, depending on how the test scores will be used, it is sometimes important to evaluate a test’s performance based on different metrics. Take a test of English language ability required for immigration for example, if the test is used as the first step to screen in proficient applicants who will be further evaluated by other criteria before granting immigration with, then NN can be trained to target at a higher level of recall. On the contrary, if the same test is used as a final gate keeper to ensure that eligible applicants, once admitted, can use English to live a functional life in the recipient country, NN can be trained to target at a higher level of precision.   
This flexibility of using NN to score for specific purposes is not granted by the traditional psychometric scoring methods like simple sum, factor analysis and item response theory. Traditionally, optimizing different performance goals for different test uses, at best, can be done by finding out different cut-off values on the scale of simple sum score or the latent scores that will give the best results for accuracy, recall or precision, based on the rule that scores ≤ cut-off are classified as negative cases and scores \> cut-off are classified as positive cases. 

4. #### **Purpose and Research Questions**

For the reasons stated above, NNs have promises as a scoring method for a short form of a test. Hence, in this study, we evaluate NN’s effectiveness as a scoring method, using the CMPA short version as a case study. The specific research questions are below: 

1) Can the NN score the short-version CMPA as well as the original full procedure in identifying respondents’ top three majors?  
2) Can the NN maximize the different performance metrics, of accuracy, recall, and precision, and still outperform the simple sum scoring method in the respective metrics?

It is crucial to point out that the objective of this study is *not* to evaluate the validity of the short-version CMPA. Our focus is on using NN to score a short form that has already been carefully selected and evaluated for validity. 

2. ### **Method** {#method}

   1. #### **Participants**

A total of 9,442 participants took the CMPA assessment online in the years 2017 and 2018\. With none excluded, 76.28% were female, 23.08% were male, 0.62% were non-binary, and 0.02% did not declare gender. As for age, 41.50% were under 16 years old, 35.37% were 17 to 18, 16.15% were 19 to 22, 4.44% were 23 to 29, and 2.64% were 30 and above. The majority (62.26%) was high school students, followed by 19.13% of university students, and the remaining18.60% were students of neither category.

2. #### **Measure**

The necessary information for CMPA for understanding the current study has already been provided in the Background section. Again, the reader can try the demo of the full version of CMPA, which does not store user data or responses, at [https://dry-retreat-23166.herokuapp.com/](https://dry-retreat-23166.herokuapp.com/).

3. #### **Analysis**

   1. ##### **Multilabel NN** 

The type of NN used for this study was a variant of NN called the Multilabel Neural Networks (MNNs), where the “multi” refers many outcomes to be predicted (whether the 50 major was in a person’s the top three as identified by the original full CMPA procedure). As shown in Figure 3.2, the input data (predictors) were the 99 Likert-type items in the short version, three items for each of the 33 (general) majors. For each respondent, the MNN would output fifty probabilities, one for each (specific) major. These predicted probabilities then were used to classify into binary outcomes of Yes (Positive) if the probability of a major being in one’s top three is \> 0.5 or No (Negative) if the probability of a major is ≤ 0.5. Then the individuals’ classified outcomes for each major were compared to the outcomes determined by the original full CMPA procedure to compute the performance of the MNNs with.   
**Figure 3.2** *Excerpt of Data Used in Fitting NNs*  
 ![][image6]  
Note. *Edu1* is the first Likert-type item for Education; *CS2* is the second Likert-type item for Computer Science, and so on. Stat is Statistics. *Edu Top 3?* is a dummy variable, representing whether Education is in each respondent’s top three preferred majors.  
	Figure 3.1 displays the one of the MNN templates, based on which we generate the neural network (detailed in 3.2.3.4 Hyperparameter Tuning). From the top to the bottom are (1) the input layer with raw data, which are the scores of 99 Likert-type items, (2) the first hidden layer with 72 nodes, and (3) the second hidden layer with 64 nodes, and (4) the final output layer with 50 nodes. Both hidden layers are marked “dense” layers because all the weights (edges) from all the nodes in previous layer to all the nodes in the next layer are freely estimated. Though not shown, all the nodes have biases (intercepts) that are also all freely estimated.  
As will be detailed later, we used hyperparameter tuning, which involves automatically generating many (around 2000\) MNNs that may have different number of layers and number of nodes in each layer to search for the best solutions, i.e., the best accuracy, recall, and precision, respectively.  
In Figure 3.1, the activation functions for dense layer-1 and \-2 are both ReLU, which equals 0 if the resultant values up to the previous layer are ≤ 0, otherwise the resultant values will be used. The ReLU is the mostly used activation function for hidden layers because they are found to enhance computational efficiency and yield good prediction performance (e.g., Chollet, 2017; Ketkar, 2017). The activation function for the output layer is the sigmoid (logistic) function because these values need to be transformed into probabilities, ranging from 0 to 1\. For all MNNs trained in the current study, the choices of activation functions are the same as Figure 3.1.  
Also shown in Figure 3.1, the values of the nodes in a layer are subject to batch normalization before they serve as the predictors for the next layer. As the name suggests, the normalization puts the predicted values of the nodes on the same scale. This simple procedure has been found to increase prediction accuracy (Santurkar et al., 2018). Batch normalizations were done for the nodes in the hidden layers when training all the MNNs in the current study.  
The output layer gives an NN the title “multilabel” because, unlike a regular neural network which can be written as a single equation for two outcomes, there were 50 outcome variables for each of the 50 majors, each indicating “whether a major is in one’s top three.” The following two equations express the algorithms leading to the output layer of probabilities for the two majors, Education and Psychology, as examples,   
P(Education\_in\_top3 \= 1| X)= SW''TB(RW'TB(R WTX \+ b)+b')+b''*.*  
P(Psychology\_in\_top\_3 \= 1| X)= SW'''''TB(RW''''TB(R W'''TX \+ b''')+b'''')+b'''''*.*  
Education\_in\_top3 is the outcome, which is a dummy variable that assumes the value of one if Education is in the respondents’ top three. The *X* is the input data on 99 Likert items, *b*s are biases, *Ws* are sets of weights. The different numbers of primes, (e.g., ' and  '') for *Ws* are to highlight the fact that the parameters can be different for different nodes. Also, the activation functions have been specified as *R* for ReLU and *S* for sigmoid, and *B* denotes batch normalization. Likewise, Psychology\_in\_top3 is a dummy variable representing whether Psychology is in the respondents’ top three. For each MNN, there are 50 such equations being trained simultaneously. See Chollet (2017) for a more detailed explanation of MNNs.  
For your reference, the *base rates*, the proportions of respondents who had a major in their top three as labeled by the original full CMPA procedure, ranged from .01 for Electronic Engineering and Chemical Engineering to .38 for Psychology, with a mean of .068 and *SD* \= .063 across the 50 majors. These base rates can be roughly understood as the popularity of the majors among the respondents. Appendix A provides a full report of these base rates for all 50 majors.  
The main objective of using MNN as a scoring machine is to maximize the agreement between the results of the short and the original versions. If the MNN can produce satisfactory performance comparable to the original full version of CMPA and better than the simple sum score, we can use MNN to score the short version in lieu of simple sum scores.   
To evaluate the performance of the MNN, for each major, the classifications by MNN (Yes/Positive \= the major is in one’s top three or No/Negative \= the major is not in one’s top three) were compared with the outcomes determined by the original full procedures. The results were tallied for all respondents in a cross-classification table as the basis for computing the performance of the MNN. For overall agreement, the accuracy rate was taken as the performance metric. Another common metric F1 for overall performance, which is the harmonic mean of recall and precision, i.e., \[2\* \# True Positives / (2\* \#True Positives \+ \# False Positives \+ \# False Negatives)\] will also be used as a supplementary criterion for comparing scoring performance.

2. ##### **Scoring for Different Uses of the Test**

 Depending on how the test results will be used, it is sometimes more important to target other performance metrics than the overall agreement. To demonstrate the NN’s flexibility to score for different performance matrices for different test uses, we also trained the MNNs to specifically target recall and precision. Targeting a high level of recall means making sure that those who are truly positive will be predicted to be positive. That is, if the original CMPA says a major is in their top three, the major will have a high probability to be predicted by the MNN to be in a respondent’s top three. Targeting a high level of precision is to make sure that those who are predicted to be positive are indeed positive. That is, among those who are predicted by MNN that a major is in their top three, the major is indeed in their top three by the original procedure.   
Note that recall and precision are antagonistic (Gordon & Kochen, 1989). Maximizing recall comes with the price of higher false positives whereas maximizing precision comes with the price of higher false negatives. Namely, targeting recall or precision is really a matter of the relative weight placed upon minimizing false negatives and false positives. Thus, we propose the loss function, weighted binary cross entropy (wBCE), which allows us to regulate the relative weight of false positive and false negative in training. The wBCE is given as,   
wBCE=-1Ni=1N\[α⋅yiln(pi)+(1-yi)ln(1-pi)\]  
where yi \= 1 if the label is positive (i.e., the major was in the respondent’s top three by the original CMPA procedure), or 0 if otherwise. The pi was the probability of outcome being positive, predicted by the MNN (i.e., the probability that the MNN thought the major would be in the respondent’s top three given the responses to the short-version items). The *N* was the number of respondents.  
The  is the relative weight, as a ratio, between the false negatives to false positives (Rezaei-Dastjerdehei et al., 2020). The higher the , the more punishment there is for false negative classifications, that is, the more encouragement for the MNN to predict positive outcomes. An extremely high  for Psychology, for example, would push the MNN to predict that Psychology is in almost everyone’s top three, boosting the recall of Psychology to a very high value. On the contrary, a low  for Psychology would make the MNN predict Yes only if it is very certain, hence favoring precision. Of course, one could also choose an  close to one to strike a balance between recall and precision. Finding different alphas for different majors to target recall and precision is the key to the success in maximizing different performance metrics. A major with a low base rate (e.g., Mechanical Engineering with .02) might need a larger alpha than a major with a higher base rate (e.g., Psychology with .34) to boost the recall to the same satisfactory level.  
Note that the MNNs were not constrained to predict what are the top threes majors, per se. Instead, the MNN’s predictions were made for all 50 majors; the MNN gave a probability ranging from 0 to 1 for each major, indicating how likely the major would have ended up in the respondent’s top three had the respondent finished the original version. The MNN classified a major as a Yes so long as the probability exceeded the decision threshold, which was set to be .50 in the current study. This led to the possibility that more or fewer than three majors were classified to be in the top three. As such, if the α weights were excessively large for all majors, the MNN would predict that all the majors were in one’s top three.  
The task of training an NN is to find the sets of parameters (weights and biases) for the neural network that will minimize the loss function and tuning the other quantities like the  that could help us maximize the performance metrics to our interest. However, the process does not guarantee useful or sensible results. For example, if we were to train an NN to indiscriminately predicts positive for all cases, it would reach 100% recall but would be useless. Likewise, we could also train an NN to predict very few positives (close to 0%) to achieve a 100% precision, which is also useless. That is, ultimately, human judgement is still needed to figure out what the “optimal” levels of recall or precision or accuracy would entail, referencing how many false positives and false negative errors the users are willing to tolerate, given their uses and purposes.

3. ##### **Adjusted Performance Metrics**

High NN performance can sometimes be achieved by chance guessing. The equations given earlier for computing the performance metrics did not take chance into account. Thus, we also used a more stringent version of the metrics, in the same logic as Cohen’s Kappa (1960), which down-adjusted the performance to exclude correct guesses occurring by chance, given as,  
Adjusted Metric=m-Em1–Em  
where the *m* is the unadjusted version of accuracy, recall or precision, *E(m)* is the expected performance if the model were blindly guessing (i.e., when the predictions were completely independent of the given data).

4. ##### **Hyperparameter Tuning**

Hyperparameters are user-determined values for setting up the structure of NN, e.g., the number of layers and nodes for each layer. Although technically not trained based on the given data, they have pivotal implications on the NN’s success. Unfortunately, there is a lack of analytical method to determine the hyperparameters with. Some automated strategies for searching the best hyperparameters are available such as grid, random, and genetic searches. For the current study, the hyperparameters that needed to be tuned included the number of layers, the number of nodes each layer, and the alpha weight in the loss function, while all the others are specified as Figure 3.1.  
Our hyperparameter tuning was first informed by manual trial and error, then it was more systematically searched using a genetic algorithm we developed, as shown in Figure 3.3. Figure 3.3 uses dogs with different traits (or balloon dogs or hot dogs) to represent different NNs with different hyperparameter settings. Our genetic algorithm first generated 30 initial MNNs with random hyperparameter settings, so the pool size started at 30\. Then, after the 30 MNNs were trained, the best performing ten MNNs were kept and allowed to reproduce while the bottom 20 were culled out. The ten that were kept were then randomly paired ten times, each time producing one child that inherited some of the hyperparameters from each of its parent, resulting in ten children being produced, making the pool size 20 (i.e., ten parents and ten children). Before adding to the pool, all the hyperparameters of all the children were added a random, small number to imitate random mutations and evolution in the natural world. Then we added ten more brand new NNs with different randomly generated hyperparameter settings to replenish the pool size to 30 (ten parents, ten children, ten from outside). The same culling and reproduction cycle was repeated 65 times, each time the MNNs/hyperparameters that survived would become better at maximizing the targeted performance metric, and then we reaped the fittest of them all after generations of evolution and used it to evaluate MNN’s scoring performance. These processes were done for finding the MNNs that optimized performance metrics of accuracy, recall, and precision, separately. For a detailed explanation of how genetic algorithms generally work, see e.g., Xiao et al. (2020).

5. ##### **Ensuring Generalization \- Cross-Validation & Regularizing**

Another common issue with NNs is overfitting (e.g., Salloum et al., 2020), where the trained algorithm becomes so accurate in predicting the given sample and fails to generalize to new samples, thus failing the goal of future prediction. To prevent overfitting, a device called regularization term are often added to the loss function to discourage finding parameters that have too much leverage (e.g., Murugan & Durairaj, 2017; Zaremba et al., 2014). This kind of regularizes were not used in the present study because they did not improve the generalization performance.  
Instead, we adopted the K-fold cross-validation procedure (e.g., Baykan & Yılmaz, 2011; Chollet, 2017; Géron, 2019\) to guard against overfitting and improve generalizability. With *K* \= 5, the training of a MNN was done for five times as shown in Figure 3.4. To do so, the full dataset was divided into *K* \+ 1 equal-sized parts, with each part contained data of 1574 respondents. Each time of training, the parameters were only updated with information from the *train data* to minimize the loss function with. Then, the parameter estimates were used to generate predictions evaluated with the *validation data*, yielding new results that were then used to adjust the training in the next round. In each round, trained parameters were also used to predict the *test data,* which were reserved to not to be used for training or validation. The final performance of the MNN was the average over the five-time results based on the test data.

6. ##### **Baseline for Performance Evaluation (Simple Sum)**

To demonstrate the effectiveness and flexibility of neural network as a scoring mechanism, the performance of the simple sum, the most common method for scoring a short form in practice, was calculated as the baseline for comparison. In reminder, the short form of CMPA intended to use stage-one results to predict what would have been of the full assessment. The simple sum for a major was the sum over the three item scores for that major in the short-version CMPA. The majors would be classified as Yes/Positive if their sum scores were ranked top three. Then, the performance of simple sum on accuracy, recall, and precision, evaluated against the outcomes from the original full CMPA, will be used as the bassline to compare MNN’s performance with.
