4. ### **Discussion** {#discussion}

The current study showcased the feasibility and flexibility of NNs in scoring a short form of an assessment, using the College Major Preference Assessment as an illustrative example. The MNN trained for specific performance goals did outperform the simple sum method by a considerable margin. This conclusion still holds after taking chance into account using the adjusted performance metrics as criteria. These findings highlight the true merits of the NN as a scoring method for specific test uses and purposes.   
Although presented in the context of scoring a short form, the present method is applicable to scoring a full form for specific performance goals for different uses as well. Moreover, the short form can be any subset of items from the original form if the rationales and validity for the subset are provided.  
Using the simple sum, the short-version CMPA already produced a high average accuracy rate of 91%. Although not the intention of this paper, this finding provided an off-label validity evidence, indirectly supporting the selection of only the Likert-type items to assess preference over 50 college majors.   
There are a few caveats in the current study. Firstly, since the focus of this study was on demonstrating the feasibility and flexibility of an NN as a scoring method, we did not work out the best algorithm that could guarantee the highest performance. Instead, we simply modified the available default methods in the software packages. One such example is hyperparameter tuning, within 65 generations and a pool size of 30 MNNs, admittedly, we were unable to obtain an adjusted F1 that outperformed the baseline significantly. Such result could have been obtained, had we allowed for a larger pool size and longer training time.  
Secondly, as mentioned in the Results section, we did obtain MNN results with a perfect adjusted recall and adjusted precision of 1.0. This was because those two MNNs predicted all individuals as positive or as negative. This may be seen as the atheoretical nature of NNs and of machine learning, in general, such that an NN will achieve the goal regardless of whether the result is sensible or useful. Thus, hyperparameter tuning requires the users to constraint the values to be reasonable to produce practically sensible and useful outcomes. Therefore, even though being perceived and named as *machine* learning, human supervision is required to carefully choose the machine learning solution that fits the researcher’s purposes.  
Finally, a long-standing criticism against NNs is that the mechanism of prediction is a black box. It has been shown that a neural-network-based credit card issuing decision system is excluding an applicant based on race, exacerbating racism in North America (Zou & Schiebinger, 2018\) or generally when its exhibited intelligence was reliant on information that had nothing to do with the main task (called “Clever Hans predictors”, Lapuschkin, et al., 2019). Hence, when using NN as a scoring method, justification of the choice of the input variables, i.e., a valid selection of the items, should be done prior to using NN to prevent biased or unfair predictions.   
Future studies could focus on identifying or developing alternative hyperparameter tuning methods that could improve the performance and accelerate computation. NNs could also be compared to more advanced scoring method than simple sums, such as item response theory or factor analysis. Although scoring based on item response theory is not amenable to different performance metrics, it is possible to compare the overall classification accuracy, recall and precision if different cut-offs on the latent ability score scale is carefully chosen to maximize each. Finally, we would like to explore whether the explanatory methods in artificial intelligence and traditional statistics, and in combination, can be used as a diagnostic tool for examining the behaviors of NN’s when being used as a scoring method. 

4. ## **Explaining a Neural Network with Perturbation and Pratt’s Measure: An Example with Assessing College Major Preference Assessment** {#explaining-a-neural-network-with-perturbation-and-pratt’s-measure:-an-example-with-assessing-college-major-preference-assessment}

This chapter is written as a stand-alone manuscript for submission to a peer-reviewed journal. Some of the content may be the same as that in Chapters 1 and 2 of this dissertation. 

1. #### **Overview and Problem Definition**

The purpose of this paper is to propose a method for examining whether the results of a supervised neural network (NN) make good sense, i.e., whether the input variables behave in the way they are supposed to.  
Neural networks are often criticized as a “Black Box,” with their predictions accurate but underlying mechanisms essentially opaque. The coefficients (i.e., weights and biases) are deemed difficult to interpret; thus, the actual contributions of the input variables to the prediction are unknown. Consequential decisions made based on such NN could be problematic. For example, an NN can deny a credit card application based on race (e.g., Zou and Schiebinger, 2018).   
This proposed method combines the technique of perturbation intervention with the Pratt’s measures. Perturbation, a technique in explainable artificial intelligence (AI), selectively changes part of the input variables to see the changes in values affect the prediction results. Pratt’s measures, a technique in regression analysis, order the relative importance of the input variables (predictors). To combine the two techniques for NNs, perturbations are done first to create a data set that can be analyzed by a linear regression so that the Pratt’s measures can be computed for the input variables.   
We will detail the method and showcase it in the context of an NN-based method for scoring a short form of a psychological assessment – College Major Preference Assessment (CMPA). Though demonstrated with a case study set in the rather specific scenario of checking the validity of using an NN to score an assessment, this method is generally applicable to any NN. 

2. #### **Explainable AI**

The current work can be situated in the broad area of *Explainable AI,* which is a movement urging that AI be human understandable, especially when consequential decisions are to be made based on its results (e.g., Samek et al., 2019). Note that we simply use the term “explanation” for the sake of communication simplicity, acknowledging the nuances in meaning related to other terms like “interpretation” and “understandability” distinguished by some philosophical work (e.g., Miller, 2019; Mueller et al., 2019). Even with simplicity intended, it is important to point out different ways that the term “explainable” could refer to in the AI literature.  
The first is *self-explanatory*, meaning that an AI is straightforward and easy to understand. This type of explainable AI avoids methods like NN that uses complex algorithms to maximize prediction performance at the price of uninterpretable relationships (e.g., Buhrmester et al., 2021). For the sake of explainability, users choose methods that are inherently simple and self-explanatory, such as conventional regression, but often at the sacrifice of superior performance (e.g., Paliwal, & Kumar, 2011).  
The second meaning for the term explainable AI is *self-explaining,* meaning that one develops an AI that includes an agent to explain its own decision-making process (i.e., Anderson et al., 2018; LeCun et al., 2015; Miller, 2019). For example, Miller (2019) trained an AI that used text (the agent) to find out that it did not classify a picture as a spider because it could only detect six legs.   
The third way to understand the term explainable AI is that an AI is *being explained*. That is, the explanation focuses on understanding the behavior of an NN that is already trained when the input variables were selected a priori according to framework (e.g., loose theory, themes, or data collection design). It is this kind of explainable AI that the current paper is going to propose. 

3. #### **What “Explainable” Means in the Current Study?**

For the current study, the term “explainable” means the ability of a method to show the *relative importance of the input variables* of a trained NN, where the input variables were selected with some framework in mind. This working definition is inspired by Goebel and colleagues’ conceptual framework (2018; see their Figure 6\) that emphasizes the ability to identify the input variable(s) based on which an AI made judgements. Also, we use the term *behavior/behave* loosely to mean “what the NN does” or “how the NN makes predictions,” which some other scholars might call a “function” (e.g., Kumar, 1994), as in a function-based design.  
Specifically, the current study trained a *multilabel* *neural network* (MNN) to predict the original outcomes of CMPA, i.e., whether a major is in a person’s top three, with only the responses to the short version items as the input variables. The short version was developed to economize on the time and burden for completing the original full CMPA. We trained two sets of MNNs separately to maximize the accuracy and recall on the same data. Then, we examined whether the trained MNNs behaved as we anticipated using our proposed method. We looked at, the relative importance of, for example, the Computer Science items in the short form to the accuracy rate in predicting Computer Science being in respondents’ top three choices, as assessed (labeled) by the original CMPA.   
The following introduction quickly reviews serval selected methods of explainable AI under the third meaning, i.e., AI being explained. Subsequently, we move to the working example of an MNN-based mechanism for scoring the CMPA short version. There, both the original version and short version will be described with enough details to understand the working example. Finally, we review Pratt’s measures (Pratt, 1987), which will be used to rank the relative importance of the input variables.

4. #### **The Need for “Explainable” NN and Existing Methods**

Along with their use in industry (e.g., Sampaio et al., 2019), NNs have served as a powerful and flexible tool for data analysis in various academic fields, including Psychology (e.g., Grossberg, & Mingolla, 1986; Starzomska, 2003; Shultz, 2003; see a proposal by the emerging field of Psychoinformatics by Montag et al. (2016), Education (e.g., Cazarez & Martin, 2018; Tang et al., 2016; Valko, & Osadchyi, 2020), and Ecology (Colasanti, 1991; Edwards & Morse, 1995; Lek et al., 1996b; Lek et al., 2000).  
The reason for NNs’ popularity, as often cited, is their state-of-the-art performance in solving practical problems of prediction and classification (e.g., Abu-Naser et al., 2015; Osman, 2016; Perkins et al., 1995; Stevens et al., 1999\) and handling non-linearity in the real-world data (e.g., Chollet, 2017; Lek et. al., 1996b; Özesmi, & Özesmi, 1999; Tu, 1996). Most impressively, the users can do so without having to program the rules explicitly; the NN learns them itself from data (e.g., Lau et al. 2019). For example, Ibrahim and Rusli (2007) found neural network the best model at predicting the cumulative grade point average among students compared with linear regression and decision tree models. As another example, Perkins et al. (1995) attested to the possibility that NNs can be trained to predict the difficulty level of test items in a reading comprehension test consistently with typical psychometric method. Valko and Osadchyi (2020) proposed a framework under which NNs could aid in building an individualized education process for each student, maximizing their fitness and success.   
As useful as they are, neural networks are criticized as essentially a “Black Box” (e.g., Buhrmester, Münch, & Arens, 2021; Müller, Hoffman, Clancey, Emrey, & Klein, 2019; Shwartz-Ziv, & Tishby, 2017; Dayhoff, & DeLeo, 2001; Shwartz-Ziv, & Tishby, 2017; Zhang, Beck, Winkler, Huang, Sibanda, & Goyal, 2018; Paliwal, & Kumar, 2011; Oh, Schiele, & Fritz, 2019\) due to their lack of “interpretability”, intuitively defined here as the understandability to human users (see a discussion of the nuances of the term by Miller, 2019). In sensitive areas such as medical decisions, “\[t\]he reality … reveals an inability of deep learned systems to communicate effectively with their users” (Goebel et al., 2018, p. X). Indeed, there might be a trade-off between interpretability and prediction performance such that the more useful the model is, the harder it is for it to produce explainable predictions (e.g., Linardatos, Papastefanopoulos, & Kotsiantis, 2021).  
The lack of the understanding of the black box can be a serious problem, especially when the NN-assisted decisions are consequential (e.g., Dayhoff & DeLeo, 2001; Gunning & Aha, 2019; Müller et al., 2019). Zou and Schiebinger (2018), for example, found an NN-based AI system that rejects credit card applications based on a person’s race, which exemplifies “algorithmic discrimination” (Serna et al., 2019). This lack of interpretability is particularly unacceptable in an academic setting where explanation often outweighs prediction as a purpose. For example, in the application of psychometrics, the lack of interpretability makes it hard to know if the interpretation and use of an NN-based scoring mechanism are valid. In fact, a few attempts to “open up the black box” of a neural network did reveal cases where a neural-network-based AI was reliant on information that had nothing to do with the main task (e.g., Lapuschkin et al., 2019).   
Thus, it is paramount to open the black box and make sure the behavior of an NN is understood before using it to make important decisions (e.g., Arrieta et al. 2020; Doran et al., 2017; Holzinger et al., 2018). Doing so not only enhances the interpretability but also the replicability of NNs (Holzinger et al., 2017). Furthermore, explainability serves to enhance the control of the debugging process, facilitate knowledge discovery, and galvanize improvements (Adadi & Berrada, 2018).  
To explain an NN, past attempts have converged on the goal of interpreting the relative contributions of input variables. Distilled and reorganized from various reviews (e.g., Angelov et al., 2021; Müller et al., 2019; Samek et al., 2017; Sung, 1998; Vilone & Longo, 2020; Yang et al., 2022), the methods can really be categorized as three broad categories (a) analytic, (b) intervention-based, and (c) auxiliary methods. These first two categories are usually, though not necessarily, done with mutual exclusivity, while auxiliary methods are adopted alongside either (a) or (b).

1. ##### **Analytic Methods**

Analytic methods mathematically derive the relative contributions of the input variables to the output. The partial derivative method (e.g., Dimopoulos et al., 1999), perhaps the most intuitive, calculates the partial derivative of the output with respect to each input variable, using backpropagation, given an activation function. The connection weight method partitions and multiplies the connection weights between each hidden neuron with the output variable to reason about the relative bearing of each connection path on the output (Garson, 1991; Gevrey et al., 2003; Goh, 1995). In similar spirits, Montavon et al. (2017) used Tylor expansions to decompose the effect of each input variable on the output at every point of the connection. Besides, there are also function-based (e.g., Simonyan & Zisserman, 2014\) and structure-based methods (e.g., Binder et al., 2016\) that deal with the mathematical underpinnings of the machine learning training process different from the traditional Taylor Expansions or partial derivatives. Ensemble methods subset the data several times, develop a simple model that approximate how the full model behaves in the subset of the data in each subset, and visualize the simple models re-assembled to make sense of the full picture (e.g., Ribeiro et al., 2016).

2. ##### **Intervention-based Methods**

The methodology we propose in this paper is intervention-based. In broad strokes, intervention-based methods manipulate the input variables to see the effects on the output to understand an AI’s behavior. Though under different names of sensitivity analysis (e.g., Jahandideh-Tehrani et al., 2020; Park et al., 2007; Scardi & Harding, 1999; Schleiter et al., 1999\) or perturbed methods (e.g., Scardi & Harding, 1999), this kind of method changes the values of the input variables to see the corresponding changes in the prediction outcomes. Specific techniques like stepwise sensitivity analysis (e.g., Balls et al., 1996; Maier, & Dandy, 1996\) and profile analysis (e.g., Lek et al., 1996a; Lek et al., 1996b) do so in a more systematic way, changing some while fixing some of the input variables before others, step by step. Others like randomization optimization method resamples the data enough times to calculate the empirical values of connection weights and compares the obtained connection weights with them, so that the users can eliminate input variables with non-significant weights (e.g., Horel & Giesecke, 2019; Hu et al., 2008; Olden, & Jackson, 2002; Su et al., 2018).

3. ##### **Auxiliary methods** 

Auxiliary methods are techniques which are themselves not explaining the NN but applied in conjunction with the other methods. Neural interpretation diagrams (Özesmi & Özesmi, 1999\) are simple graphs visualizing the weights of the NN. For NNs being used for computer vision, visual bag of words and related methods are ways to cluster parts of the image (usually pixels) to identify meaningful units such as the pixels representing the beak of a bird in an image (e.g., Filliat, 2007). There is also textualization techniques to describe the judgements made by the AI.

5. #### **Working Example: MNNs for Short Version CMPA**

The working examples are set in the context of training multilabel neural networks, with the short-version items as the input variables, to predict whether the 50 majors would be in one’s top three favorites had the respondents taken the original full version of CMPA. That is, we perceived a MNN as a scoring machine for the short version of CMPA to predict the results (labels) of the original CMPA. In the following, we first briefly introduce the short and original versions of CMPA, followed by the MNNs used to score the short version.  
The CMPA (iKoda, 2017\) was developed to help individuals identify their preference over 50 college majors. It is an online adaptive assessment, meaning that the items being delivered are increasingly personalized to an individual according to their previous responses. The validity and reliability evidence for the CMPA was provided by Wu (2021; Mao et al., 2022).  
The original version of CMPA has two stages of assessments. The first stage consists of three sets of 33 Likert-type items with a total of 99 items. Questions in each set ask the respondents to indicate the extent to which they would like to learn a certain topic related to each of the 33 majors. Stage-2 uses forced-choice items to narrow down each respondent’s choices from stage-one by forcing the respondents to choose between two majors each time. It is important to notice that some of the 33 majors are split into multiple more specific majors in stage-2. For example, if the major, General Business, is screened in for a respondent by the end of stage-1, it is split into specific majors of Accounting, Economics, Marketing, and Business for the respondent to choose. Thus, the total number of specific majors that CMPA assesses is 50 rather than 33\.   
The final results of CMPA are rankings of top three majors determined by the number of times the respondent chose a particular major in stage-2. See an online demo version at [https://dry-retreat-23166.herokuapp.com/](https://dry-retreat-23166.herokuapp.com/)).  
Because the stage-2 paired forced-choices was more cognitively burdensome, the CMPA development team used the short version, which included only 99 Likert-type items in stage-1, in lieu of the original version. The short version was scored using MNN (Wu et al., 2022), i.e., using the predicted probabilities to identify one’s top three favorites. The MNN scoring method was found to be effective in identifying the top three majors determined by the original CMPA (Wu et al., 2022). 

6. #### **Pratt’s Measures**

The Pratt’s measure, first introduced by Pratt (1987), is a useful statistical tool for indicating the relative importance of the independent variables in a multiple regression (Thomas et al., 1998). It is computed as the product of the first order Pearson’s correlation () and the standardized patrial regression coefficient β between an independent variable and the outcome variable. That is, for each independent variable *p*, the importance measure is simply pp. In addition to its simplicity in computation, it has been proven mathematically to have the additive property such that 1Ppp=R2 , *p* \= 1, 2, *P*. That is, the Pratt’s measures across all the P independent variables will sum up to the R-squared value, i.e., the proportion of variance explained by the regression model, even when the independent variables are correlated with one another. This property has two interconnected benefits: (1) Pratt’s measures have already considered the redundant information among the independent variables, and (2) each measure has a very intuitive meaning, which is the amount of variance explained by the specific independent variable and can be used to indicate its relative importance in the regression.

7. #### **The Proposed Method for Explaining NN** 

Given the benefits of Pratt’s measures, the question is how to incorporate this technique into perturbation, the intervention-based approach we adopted for our proposed method of explainable AI. The following describes the steps of the proposed method:  
Step-1. Disable part of the input by randomly selecting a certain number of the input variables and record the random selection results as a dummy variable (1 \= selected; 0 \= disabled/not selected).  
Step-2. Train an NN using the same settings (e.g., number of layers, nodes, activation functions, etc.) as the NN one aims to explain, taking only the randomly selected subset as the input variables. Record performance metric of interest (e.g., accuracy, recall, or precision).   
Step-3. Repeat Step-1 and Step-2 many times, say *N* \= 5000 times. Compile a data set for Step-4, such that records from Step-1 are used as independent variables and those from Step-2 is the dependent variable (or variables, if there are more than two performance metrics), as shown in Figure 4.1.  
Step-4. Run a regression based on a complied data set with *N* rows of records, where the independent variables are the dummy variables, representing whether the input variables are selected in Step-1, and the dependent variable is one performance metric in Step-2.  
Step-5. Calculate Pratt’s measures and evaluate whether the relative importance of input variables makes sense.  
The proposed method will be demonstrated in the Method and Results sections with the CMPA as a working example. Specifically, the MNNs used the 99 Likert items in the short version to predict the 50 majors labeled by the original CMPA procedure. To show the effectiveness and feasibility of the proposed method, we purposefully tried out two kinds of performance metrics: accuracy and recall. Accuracy \= \[(\# True Positives \+ \# True Negative) /\# Total Cases\], showing the proportion of total correct predictions over all predictions. Recall \= \[\# True Positives / \[\# True Positives / \# Actual Positives in the Data\], showing how likely the model is to correctly identify a major if it is indeed in one’s top three (Yes \= Positive, No \= Negative). Since recall is known to be inflated by excessive guessing of Positive, we have adjusted recall using the following formula to correct for chance:   
Recalladjusted=Recall-Recallchance1-Recallchance.  
This adjustment is congruent with the logic of Cohen’s Kappa (Cohen, 1960). Hereafter, we refer to adjusted recall simply as recall.

2. ### **Method** {#method-1}

   1. #### **Participants and Measure** 

A total of 9,442 participants took the CMPA assessment online in the years 2017 and 2018\. Among them, 76.28% were female, 23.08% were male, 0.62% were non-binary, and 0.02% did not declare gender. As for age, 41.50% were under 16 years old, 35.37% were 17 to 18, 16.15% were 19 to 22, 4.44% were 23 to 29, and 2.64% were 30 and above. The majority (62.26%) was high school students, followed by 19.13% of university students, and the remaining18.60% were students of neither category. The necessary information about CMPA to understand the current study with has already been provided in the Background section.

Despite the good performance for many majors, like most NNs, the results of both MNNs were difficult to interpret; it was unclear whether the prediction was consistent with CMPA’s design. This difficulty is obvious given the massive number of weights and biases (15394) for an MNN with only two hidden layers that had 72 and 64 nodes, respectively. It is almost impossible for the human mind to intuitively detect a pattern as to how the input variables contributed to the prediction accuracy and recall. That is, we were unable to examine whether the three Likert-type items for Psychology, for example, were indeed the relatively more important input variables for predicting whether Psychology would be in one’s top three. Therefore, we applied our perturbation-Pratt’s measure method to *explain* MNN-1 and MNN-2. 

3. #### **The Proposed Method with the Current Case**

We conducted the first three steps laid out earlier for the proposed method to generate the data set for regression and computing the Pratt’s measures. For Step-1, in each trial of perturbation, 49 out of 99 total input variables (about half) were randomly disabled for the second step of MNN training. The reason for selecting about half of the input variables was to maximize variation of selection. The selection results were recorded as 99 dummy variables for the 99 items (1 \= selected and 0 \= disabled/not selected). For Step-2, a new MNN with the same hyperparameter setting as MNN-1 was trained with only the 50 selected (not disabled) input variables, and 50 accuracy rates for the 50 specific majors (analogous to the accuracy rates in Table XXX) were computed to be used later as the dependent variables in later linear regressions. For Step-3, the first two steps were repeated 5000 times, resulting in 5000 accuracy rates for each of the 50 majors. Notice that, for all 5000 trials, the training was constrained under the same hyperparameter settings of MNN-1, however, with a different set of fifty randomly selected input variables in each trial.   
Figure 4.1 shows the data set generated under MMN-1 setting. The first column indicates the identification of perturbation trials, and the last 50 columns (AccMajor1 to AccMajor50) indicate the resultant accuracy rates for the 50 specific majors, respectively. The remaining 99 columns, Item1Major1 to Item3Major33, were dummy variables indicating whether an input variable was disabled or selected in each perturbation trial.   
**Figure 4.1** *Dataset generated under MMN-1 Setting*  
![][image9]  
To generate data for MNN-2, we conducted the same first three steps except that the MMN-2 hyperparameter setting was used in training all 5000 trials, and the recall rates were computed to be used as the dependent variables for regression**.**

4. #### **Regression Analysis and Pratt’s Measures**

To obtain the standardized partial regression coefficients needed for computing the Pratt’s measures, we ran fifty regressions, each with the accuracy rate of one specific major as the dependent variable, based on the data set generated under MNN-1 setting. The equation below is an example regression equation for accuracy rates of Major1 (AccMajor1) obtained under the setting of MNN-1,   
AccMajor1= b0+b1Item1Major1 \+b2Item2Mjaor1 \+b3Item3Major1  
                                   \+ b4Item1Major2 \+b5Item2Mjaor2 \+b6Item3Major2  
                 \+ ....................+ .................... \+ ....................   
                                   \+ b97Item1Major3+b98Item2Mjaor3+b99Item3Major3  
where 0 was the intercept, which indicates base accuracy rate for Major1, i.e., the accuracy rate with no input information. The b coefficients with subscripts 1 to 99 were the standardized regression coefficients of the independent variables, i.e., the 99 dummy variables of whether the items were selected or disabled.  
In all the 50 regressions for the 50 majors, the independent variables were always the same 99 dummy variables, indicating the selected/disabled status of the 99 items in the training that led to differences in the accuracy rates over the 5000 trials. The same regression model was applied to the data set prepared under MNN-2 setting, except, this time, the 50 dependent variables were the recall rates, one for each major. Because both accuracy and recall rates were normally distributed, we used ordinary least squares as the estimator for all regression analyses. 

5. #### **Pratt’s Measures**

For each regression for each major, we calculated the Pratt’s measure for each independent variable, using the product term ρpp where p \= 1…99; the p is the zero-order correlation between the independent variable *p* with the dependent variable, i.e., the accurate rate for MMN-1 setting and recall for MMN-2 setting; the p is the standardized partial regression coefficient of independent variable *p*, controlling for all the other 98 independent variables. Thus, the value of  ρpp indicates the amount of variance in accuracy or recall that was attributable to the inclusion of item *p* in the MNN.   
Because of the additive property of Pratt’s measures, the Pratt’s measures will sum up to the *R2* value of the regression model, the Pratt’s measures can be further normalized. That is, the *standardized* Pratt’s measure for the independent variable *p* is  ppRModel2. As such, instead of summing up to the RModel2*,* the standardized Pratt’s measures sum up to 1\. The standardized Pratt’s measure of the pth independent variables indicates the proportion of R2 the pth independent variable contributes to. We will report standardized Pratt’s measures here that are comparable across all majors. 

6. #### **Software**

The perturbation data generation process was conducted using self-developed code available here for replication: [https://github.com/husohome/career\_ml](https://github.com/husohome/career_ml). The implementation relies on the open-source programming language *Python* *3.8* (Van Rossum, 1995), with *Anaconda* Distribution (Anaconda Software Distribution, 2020), GPU-enabled *Tensorflow-gpu* (Abadi, 2016\) and *Keras* (Chollet, 2018\) packages for the Neural Networks, and *Pandas* (McKinney, 2011\) and *Numpy* (Van Der Walt et al., 2011\) for data preprocessing.  
	The preparation of regression data and regression analyses were conducted in the *R* language (R Core Team, 2021), with the open-source packages: *dplyr* (Wickham et al., 2021**)** and *reshape2* **(**Wickham, 2007**)** for data manipulation and utilities and *ggplot2* (Wickham, 2016), *RColorBrewer* **(**Neuwirth, 2014**)** for visualization, *glue* (Hester, 2020\) for string manipulation. The R code is available on the first author’s GitHub repository:  [https://github.com/husohome/career\_ml/tree/master/perturbation](https://github.com/husohome/career_ml/tree/master/perturbation)**.**

3. ### **Results** {#results-1}

Figure 4.2 visualizes the results of the proposed method under MNN-1 setting for optimizing accuracies, with seven majors selected as the illustrative examples in separate panels. The Y-axis shows the standardized Pratt’s measures, and the X-axis shows the independent variables in the regression, i.e., the selected/disabled status of the 99 items in training MNN-1. Taking Psychology as an example, the three independent variables that recorded the selected/disabled of the three Psychology items had the highest Pratt’s measures, compared to the other 96 independent variables in the short version of CMPA. The direct interpretation is this: the selection/disabling of these three Likert-type items in training MNN-1had the most influence on the prediction accuracy of whether Psychology was in a respondent’s top three.  
This result of the Pratt’s measures can further be argued as evidence for judging whether using MMN-1 to score the short-version CMPA is valid for prediction accuracy. For example, it can be seen in Figure 4.2 that, for Psychology, the classification of whether the major was in one’s top three was mostly based on the input information of the three Psychology items, hence the results provide validity evidence for using MNN-1 to score Psychology for prediction accuracy. Similar validity evidence could be found in Figure 4.2 for Criminology, Education, and Accounting, where the items that had the highest standardized Pratt’s measures were the three items in the short-version CMPA that were supposed to assess the preferences for the corresponding majors.  
Figure 4.2 shows the unexpected but sensible patterns of using MMN-1 to score for prediction accuracy of Civil Engineering. In addition to the expected items (General Engineering-1, \-2, and \-3), the selection/disabling of Architecture-1 also contributed noticeably to the prediction accuracy of whether Civil Engineering would be in a respondent’s top three. This result makes sense given that Civil Engineering and Architecture both pertain to buildings. In contrast, for Gender Studies and Electronic Engineering, Figure 4.2 provides weak validity evidence for using MMN-1 to score the short-version CMPA for prediction accuracy. This is because the three items that were supposed to be more important did not end up with noticeably larger Pratt’s measures, despite MNN-1’s high prediction accuracy of .96 for Gender Studies and .99 for Electronic Engineering. Many other items that were not designed to assess these two majors and were irrelevant to Electronic Engineering also contributed to the prediction accuracy.   
No matter the strength of validity in using MNN-1 to score different majors for prediction accuracy, the proposed method provides human digestible and comprehensible measures for evaluating the behavior of MNN-1.  
**Figure 4.2** *The Results of the Proposed Method for Seven Example Majors on MNN-1 Accuracy* 

*Note.* Preference for Accounting was assessed by the three items of General Business, and preference for Electrical Engineering and Civil Engineering was assessed by the three items of General Engineering in the short version of CMPA.   
Figure 4.3 summarizes the overall pattern of the standardized Pratt’s measures across all fifty majors, instead of seven selected majors as in Figure 4.2 for MNN-1 accuracy rates. The values of standardized Pratt’s measures were indicated by the different shades of green in the cells, i.e., darker greens mean higher Pratt’s measures. The numbers in the cells are the values of standardized Pratt’s measures rounded to the second decimal but without showing the decimal point, e.g., a cell value of 33 means the standardized Pratt’s measure \= 0.33. For clarity, the cells that had standardized Pratt’s measures \< .005 (very trivial) are shown in white color without showing the values. Also, the boxes outlined by gray borders in Figure 4.3 are visual aids to highlight the cells that were supposed to have relatively high standardized Pratt’s measures according to the CMPA design.  
As one can see, most, but not all, majors demonstrated good validity evidence for using MNN-1 to score for prediction accuracy because, the cells in the boxes are greener relatively to the cells outside of the boxes. 

**Figure 4.3** *The Full Results of the Proposed Method for All 50 Majors on MNN-1 Trained for Accuracy*  
*Note.* The results for items that assess more than one specific major would take up more than three cells as outlined by the gray box. For example, the three items for General Health had Pratt’s measures for three specific majors of Health Science, Kinesiology, and Nursing.   
Figure 4.4 carries parallel information to Figure 4.2, except that Figure 4.4 shows the standardized Pratt’s measures for recall rates of MNN-2 for the seven majors selected for demonstration. By the same logic, MNN-2 appears to have used expected information to predict whether Accounting, Criminology, Education, and Gender Studies would be in one’s top three. This could, similarly, be interpreted as validity evidence for using MNN-2 to score the short-version CMPA for optimizing recall for these majors. Following the same lines of thinking, according to Figure 4.4, MNN-2 seems to have utilized sensible additional information pertinent to Electronic Engineering (the expected items for General Engineering plus additional items for Computer Science), and Civil Engineering (the expected items for General Engineering items plus additional items for Architecture). This again, could bolster the validity of using MNN-2 to score the short-version CMPA for the high recall rates for these two majors. Finally, there seems to be weak validity evidence for using MNN-2 to score Psychology for recall. This is due to the dispersed pattern of standardized Pratt’s measures across many of the 99 items in the short-version CMPA.  
**Figure 4.4** *The Results of the Proposed Method for Seven Example Majors on MNN-2 Recall* 

Parallel to Figure 4.3, Figure 4.5 shows the overall pattern of MNN-2’s behavior for all the majors. As one can see, most, but not all, majors demonstrated good validity evidence for using MNN-2 to score for prediction recall because, the cells in the boxes are greener relatively to the cells outside of the boxes.   
To summarize our demonstration for the proposed methods, the results demonstrate the feasibility of combining Pratt’s measures with perturbation-based interventions to explain an NN’s behavior in a manner that is highly understandable to humans. The proposed method is useful tool for evaluating the validity of NN as a scoring method for specific performance because it helps explain how much each input variable contributes to the performance.

4. ### **Discussion** {#discussion-1}

The current paper proposed an explainable AI method using the combined techniques of perturbation and Pratt’s measures. Based on the working example of CMPA, the results demonstrate the feasibility of employing the proposed method to produce human digestible and comprehensible patterns of the relative importance of input variables.  
To the peculiarity of the working example used in this paper, we used the patterns to check whether and to what extent the neural networks made predictions based on input variables we had wanted them to use, thus providing or withholding validity evidence for using the NN as a scoring mechanism for certain majors. For example, we checked if the NN referred to items whose content is about Electronic Engineering to make judgments about whether Electronic Engineering would be in a respondent’s top three preferred majors. We realized that even with an accuracy of 97%, the MNN did not seem to have taken advantage of electronic-engineering-related items, suggesting that the high accuracy on electronic engineering might have been “a lucky hit” or “Clever Hans”, the latter being a more common term in machine learning. The worry that good performance might be achieved accidentally, in large part, motivated the field of explainable AI, and the fact that we found evidence for the lucky hit, in turn, showed the effectiveness of our method as an explanation tool.  
The proposed method can be applied more generally to situations where visualizing relative importance of input variables would be conducive, not just for validation. For instance, in the absence of a framework (e.g., loose theory or themes) for selecting the input variables, it is possible to use it as an *exploratory* tool to find out the contributions of a set of input variables (clusters) to the outcomes and help develop a framework (e.g., loose theory or themes). For another example, one could use it to select a set of input variables that together would contribute to a satisfactory level of performance (e.g., a certain level of R-square) for developing a subscale, or simply making the NN more parsimonious.  
It is important to point that, our method differs from the typical perturbed methods reviewed in the Introduction section. That is, our method does not actually *manipulate* the *values* of the input variables; instead, it *disables* part of the input variables and use the original values of the selected variables as the input for training. This could solve the two drawbacks of a typical perturbed experiment. The first problem is that the typical perturbation methods have too many values (conditions) to experiment with. Especially for continuous variables, the decision of the which values to try on is not easy to make and often arbitrary. The second problem is that the values or combination of values of the input variables that produce the best results might not be empirically realistic, meaning the values or combinations of the input values that produced the best results could be completely counterfactual or nonsensical. Our method, in contrast, speaks directly of interpretable values – the proportion of R-square explained, which is already scaled to be within the range of zero and one for all the input variables and is intuitively easy to understand as measures of relative importance.  
The proposed method differs from a typical perturbation method in that it needs to train an NN for each trial to get to the consequent performance metrics, though under the same hyperparameter setting, because a different set of input variables is selected in each perturbation trial. This means the weights and biases may turn out to be somewhat different while keeping the hyperparameter setting constant. At the first glance, our approach might seem problematic because the weights and biases, which are contingent on the random start values of the parameters in each training trial, may be different, and the specific nodes may capture different parts of the input. However, exactly because the behavior of the specific nodes is subject to the random start values (e.g., Iyer & Rhinehart, 1999), which are haphazard anyway, we can focus on the overall behavior of the network instead. If the neural network functions the same way, predicting similarly given similar data. This consistence, even with the changes of the functionalities of the specific nodes, is achieved through constancy in hyperparameter settings. That is, by focusing on the constancy in hyperparameters (i.e., the hyperparameter settings that produced the performance shown in Table 4\.1\) as we propose, we bring the extra benefits of not having to deal with empirically impossible values produced by the existing perturbed methods.   
With the benefits come the limitations. The first and the most pronounced is that, since our method needs to retrain the neural networks for each perturbation trial, the users need to have access to the original data, not just the hyperparameter setting. This problem could arise when the person in charge of explaining a neural network is not the same person who had the data and trained the neural network. Secondly, the proposed method works better when the user knows what to look for (e.g., loose theory, themes, or data collection design) when visualizing the pattern, which is not always the case, especially for the projects where the input variables are not screened and messy. Thirdly, the perturbation-training procedure is not time efficient. On the first author’s computer with the specification, Intel 10th Gen i7 and CUDA-enabled GPU (NVIDIA GEFORCE-RTX 2060, compute capability of 7.5; [https://developer.nvidia.com/cuda-gpus](https://developer.nvidia.com/cuda-gpus)), it took 40 to 300 seconds every perturbation for the CMPA data; the training for the whole 5000 data sets took around three weeks. Of course, the efficiency in time could be improved if more powerful computers are available.  
We shall highlight a few strengths also. In the particular use case of unboxing the multilabel neural networks to score short-version CMPA, the combination of perturbation and Pratt’s measures provides digestible and interpretable visualization for how much the input variables contribute to the performance. The price to pay for the benefit is low, i.e., the method is easy to understand and implement. The idea of disabling some input information is straightforward and the computation of Pratt’s measure is simple without complicated mathematics derivation or statistical estimation.  
Furthermore, this combined method is rather permissive. If the researcher knows what to look for in a visualized pattern between the input and the outcomes, the Pratt’s measure provides critical aid in diagnostics. To know what to look for, one arguably only needs a framework (e.g., loose theory, themes, or data collection design) that can be translated into some correspondencies between the input and output variables, which is the scenario of most, if not all, studies with quantitative research, in academic settings.  
	Overall, the current method provides a simple way of better understanding neural networks’ behavior. We hope to see more intuitive and accessible methods for explaining neural network to burgeon as NN’s popularity continues to grow in quantitative research. 

5. ## **Discussion** {#discussion-2}

This chapter summarizes the findings and highlights the unique contributions of this dissertation in the context of existing pioneering fields integrating machine learning with social science research. Subsequently, it discusses limitations and future implications.

1. ### **Summary** {#summary-1}

In broad strokes, this dissertation attempts to integrate neural networks and traditional statistical methods to solve challenges in scoring a complex psychological assessment. Although the dissertation used the CMPA as the working example throughout, it intended to contribute to methodology, not to validity of CMPA, nor to the literature of college career.  
Study-1, in Chapter 3, used NNs as a scoring method for a short test form whose subset of items had been decided. The results not only highlight the NN’s superior effectiveness over the traditional simple sum scoring method, but also its flexibility in scoring for different test uses and performance metrics. Study-2, in Chapter 4, proposed a method that combines a perturbation-based technique and Pratt’s measures to order the relative importance of input variables in an NN. Though being used to diagnose the mechanism for scoring a psychological assessment, the proposed method can serve as a general tool for opening the black box of NNs and be taken advantage of for exploratory purposes, such as finding themes or clusters of input variables for developing working theories or choosing enough input variables for parsimony. 

2. ### **Pioneers in Relevant Fields**  {#pioneers-in-relevant-fields}

This dissertation is by no means a pioneering work attempting to connect machine learning and social science research. Indeed, burgeoning research in fields like psychoinformatics (e.g., Montag et al., 2016), computational psychometrics (e.g., von Davier, Mislevy, et al., 2021), and educational data mining (e.g., Romero et al., 2010\) have all dedicated themselves to similar topics and inspired my dissertation. In the following I quickly give an overview about these fields and then discuss how my dissertation related to this fields.  
Psychoinformatics emphasizes the binding of technology, especially big data, and psychological research (Markowetz et al., 2014; Montag et al., 2016; Pandeya, 2020; Yarkoni, 2012). According to the proponents, Internet of Things (IoT), human interactions with devices like smartphones and social media (Montag, Błaszkiewicz, Iet al., 2015), electronic sensors, survey apps like MTurk and Qualtrics (Yarkoni, 2012\) should all be added to the toolkit of social science researchers as they provide larger, more continuously updated, and/or more ecologically valid data that are less susceptible to researchers’ biases in designing surveys and experiments (Montag, et al., 2016). In their views, analyzing big, natural data can be especially conducive to clinical psychology research, e.g., internet addiction (Montag, Reuter, et al., 2015; Montag et al., 2017), neuroscience (Montag, 2019\) and the personality traits research (Markowetz et al., 2014). In the occasional mentions of the word psychometrics (e.g., Montag et. al, 2016), the authors referred to the assessment for clinical psychology specifically.  
Computational psychometrics was first mentioned by Alina Von Davier, at the International Conference of Machine Learning in France (Von Davier, 2015). Later, it was defined as a blend of data science techniques, computer science, and principled psychometric approaches to aid the analyses of complex data as obtained from performance assessments and technology-enhanced learning and assessment systems (von Davier, 2017). The naming of the discipline is to “capture the most essential feature of this new subdiscipline, i.e., data-driven computational algorithms, while keep\[ing\] its primary alignment \[with\] psychometrics” (von Davier, DiCerbo, et al., 2021, p. v.). With an interdisciplinary team of data scientists and psychometricians, the field made extensive efforts to delineate how exactly these complex data work together, and educating psychometricians about machine learning (e.g., Hao, & Mislevy, 2021; Hao, 2021; Wong, 2021). For example, Mislevy (2021) proposed a sociocognitive framework in which emerging forms of data could help with a holistic and interactionist understanding of the human behaviour, shedding light on the linguistic, cultural, and substantive contexts. All authors mentioned so far hinted at the potential of big, new forms of data (e.g., text mining; Flor & Hao, 2021\) informing *process-based* assessment. For instance, click patterns and log data, showing how students interact with an online course system, are all regarded as valuable data (von Davier, DiCerbo, et al., 2021).  
Educational Data Mining has the longest history (with the first workshop in 2005; Baker, & Inventado, 2014\) and there is a dedicated journal and website of it under the same name. Although data mining refers to the rather specific practice of “searching through large amounts of computerized data to find useful patterns or trends” (Merriam-Webster, n.d.), with emphasis on data discovery and retrieval (Witten & Frank, 1999), the field accepts papers on predictions (e.g., Baker & Inventado, 2014), psychometrics, statistics, visualization, and machine learning (e.g., Baker & Yacef, 2009), in addition to the classical data mining (e.g., association rule mining and sequential pattern mining, text mining; categorized by Romero and Ventura (2007). The field welcomes any attempts to help better understand students and the settings in which they learn, to enhance educational practices (see their website at ([https://educationaldatamining.org/](https://educationaldatamining.org/)). However, generally speaking, this field has preferred automated techniques to methods that need much human judgement over the process for data analysis (Baker & Inventado, 2014).  
There are also studies that may or may not particularly associate themselves with the fields that could nonetheless belong to any of the three. For example, as systematically reviewed by Kulak et al. (2018), machine learning is used for practical purposes in education such as predicting student performance, testing students more fairly, enhancing retention, facilitating administrative management, and designing effective platforms for learning and teaching. As a natural progression, there is work on the effectiveness of machine learning in such use cases (e.g., Lee, 2021). Also, educational techniques are, in turn, applied to helping students learn machine learning (Giannakos et al., 2020).  
With the slightly different foci, all the literature discussed so far sees the surge of the variety of data types such as Massive Open Online Courses (MOOC), Learning Management Systems (e.g., Canvas) and rich, unstructured text data as opportunities for educational researchers to better study human behaviour. They also welcome different degrees of use of machine learning algorithms involving more intensive computations than traditional statistical approaches.  
Given the inclusiveness of these fields, I did not see the pioneering call of these fields as specifically attached to the use of learning management system or, technology, or means of data collection, or even the use of big data. It is generally about how such fields as computer science, data science, technology, big data, and machine learning can benefit education and social science in practical and academic settings.

3. ### **The Unique Contributions of this Dissertation** {#the-unique-contributions-of-this-dissertation}

As a methodological piece, my dissertation tries to *integrate* machine learning techniques and statistical methods in social science in ways that could benefit both fields. I venture to say that the unique contributions of this dissertation are in the extension of the role that machine learning can play in social science research.  
While existing work on similar topics has significantly expedited advances in social science research, it tends to confine machine learning to either of the two roles. The first role is as an intervention, and the research is to evaluate its effectiveness. Lee (2021)’s systematic review on the effectiveness of machine translation (a subfield of machine learning) in foreign language education provides plenty of such examples. Van Lehn (2011) conducted a meta-analysis comparing the effectiveness of human tutoring and machine-learning-based intelligent tutoring systems (mostly CIRCSIM, developed by Evens et al., 1997\) on learning physiology and blood circulations for medical students. While applying machine learning as a new practical tool, they still used the canonical research methods in social and behavioral sciences with the typical ANOVA, linear models, *t* and *F* tests or even qualitative methods to analyze the new machine learning’s effectiveness.  
The second role machine learning plays is as an alternative to existing statistical method. For example, Al-Shabandar et al. (2017) used NNs to predict learning outcomes in massive open online courses. Hardgrave et al.’s work (1994) marked an early attempt to predict students’ academic success in a graduate MBA program with NNs, which they showed to have an advantage over the traditional techniques like linear regression. Alkhasawneh and Hobson (2011), similarly, predicted whether students would stay in Science and Engineering (retention rate) at a 70% accuracy with NNs and classified students according to their risk level of dropping out. More recent examples are available in Luan and Tsai (2021)’s review. In all these studies that used NNs I reviewed, machine learning was presented as the newer, better method than the traditional ones, without further integration with existing research techniques in Social Science.   
In either role, machine learning was plugged in for use as a stand-alone prediction device and was not treated as a part whose utility can be further extended or integrated with other parts to create a new tool with. That is, NN was not used to create a new tool that can do more than prediction. In this sense, the current dissertation sets out to use machine learning as an integrated part of a new methodology to solve other problems than prediction such as scoring the responses to complex psychological assessments in Chapter 3 and developing a new method of explainable AI in Chapter 4\.  
To use machine learning as an integrated part of a new methodology, what Study-1, in Chapter 3, suggested is that if we reframe a psychometric problem, like scoring a shortened test, into a prediction one, machine learning (NNs, specifically) can blend in to provide high levels of flexibility and effectiveness to solve problems that traditional psychometric techniques fall short of. To reframe the complex high-dimensional (50 majors) scoring problem into an NN prediction exercise in Study-1, I needed to re-conceptualize the problem as 50 prediction problems of whether a major was in a respondent’s top three that needed to be done simultaneously. This re-framing led to the choice of using the multilabel neural network as the potential solution. Though appearing subtle and trivial, this simple re-framing of the highly dimensional scoring problem into multi-label prediction problems is the pivotal twist that enabled me to take advantage of the benefits of NNs.   
Study-2 in Chapter 4 is another such re-framing exercise to use machine learning as an integrated part of a new methodology. In this study, I re-vamped perturbation method so that it can be coupled with simple but powerful tool of Pratt’s measures to improve the explainability – a virtue that machine learning often lacks, yet essential in social science research. Though, as reviewed in Chapter 2 and Chapter 4, there already exist movements like explainable AI natively within machine learning, they tend to use either complex mathematics that are unknown to social scientists or do not directly “explain” NNs per se. ~~The pivotal point in the second study was re-vamping perturbation so that it can be coupled with Pratt’s measures to order the importance of input variables, thus providing explanations for an NN’s behaviour.~~ The revamping of perturbation and integration it with Pratt’s measures led to easily interpretable information that others in explainable AI often struggle with (i.e., producing values that are empirically possible or nonsensical). In my judgement, the Pratt’s measures are one of the many possible manners in which tools in academic research can complement and bolster machine learning.  
Exceptions acknowledged, it is acceptable to say that machine learning, by design, is better at tackling real-life complex prediction problems, while statistical methods for social science research are better at explaining relationships and testing theories. It can be anticipated that more potential can be realized if techniques from the two sides can be integrated to complement each other. In this sense, the unique contributions of this dissertation are not merely the two specific methods proposed, but the demonstrated capacity to re-conceptualize the seemingly peculiar challenges to either field as more conceptual methodological principles so that the mechanics for bridging the two sides can be identified and built. 

4. ### **Limitations, Implications, and Future Directions** {#limitations,-implications,-and-future-directions}

The current dissertation demonstrated ways that machine learning and statistics in academic research can mutually benefit. However, due to the focus on methodological principles, much of the technical detail about hyperparameter tuning that is highly consequential on NN results in Chapter 3, hence the NN to be diagnosed in Chapter 4, was not covered. To compensate for this, the codes for my self-developed framework and tutorial is accessible on GitHub at [https://github.com/husohome/career\_ml](https://github.com/husohome/career_ml) for interested readers to review. The technical detail is better communicated via the Parselmouth of computer languages, i.e., *Python*. In addition, given the focus on psychometrics and methodology, I did not dwell on finding “the best” algorithm that could really optimize NN’s performance or computation speed. The perturbation-regression based method for Pratt’s measures in Chapter 4 took me up to three weeks to implement. Other hyperparameter tuning methods or optimizing algorithms could have produced more accurate results faster.  
Future studies could expand the joint force of machine learning and statistics in social science research to continuously help with problems in psychometrics. A near transfer, for example, would be using the NN as a scoring method maximizing other performance metrics than adjusted recall or precision. Also, though not explicitly discussed, NNs could be used to score continuous outcome variables as well, such that, instead of predicting whether a major is in one’s top three, it could predict CMPA’s original scores for each major. This would entail using a different loss function, such as the mean-squared errors. Future research could develop analogs to the performance metrics like accuracy, recall, precision, for continuous outcomes.  
Also, Study-1 is premised upon the short form items being already determined, but if granted more control over the selection of items, future research may apply NN to develop a method for assembling a short form by selecting a pre-determined percentage, say 30% of the items such that the results are the closest to the original form. This could greatly help with short form development when there are many items in an item bank. Of course, this is approach to short form development only makes sense when content coverage for validity is not a major concern. In all the suggested projects for future studies, one could additionally run a perturbation-Pratt’s measures to explain the neural networks with.  
As for the extension upon the perturbation-Pratt’s measure explanation device developed in Study-2, one way to expedite the perturbation process might be to mix in the intuition of ensemble method in explainable AI discussed in Chapter 4 under Analytic Methods, which is to use a simpler model, such as linear regression, than NN to explain the partial behaviour of the full NN in certain parts of the input variables and finally putting them together. Transferred to perturbation, this would correspond to *stratified* random disabling of the input variables, such that the input variables are divided into a few non-overlapping groups first, and the selective disabling the perturbation is applied to a certain percentage, say 50% of the input variables in each group. Each group is then calculated the Pratt’s measures to infer the NN’s local behaviour with, and finally the global behaviour of the NN is inferred by ensembling all the parts. This could be used to aid in the understanding of the behaviour of E-raters (e.g., Byrne et al., 2010), for example, and amplify their functions such that it can no longer be tricked by AI-based linguistically beautiful but academic nonsense generators like BABEL trained specifically to score high on E-raters (e.g., Perelman et al., 2014).  
In closing, as the pioneers have advocated and shown, closer collaboration from different disciplines will sparkle far reaching discoveries and innovations. With this dissertation, I hope to motivate and invite more researchers and methodologists from different camps to exchange and integrate our knowledge and skills. With the availability of more variety and large amount of data and new technology that can do real-time heavy computing, there will be many exciting opportunities and possibilities to be discovered and developed jointly.

3. **Other Technical, Software, Implementation Details for Multilabel NN**

Maximum Iterations: The slopes (*weights* in machine learning terms) and intercepts (*biases* in machine learning terms) were algorithmically adjusted to lower the value of the loss function, until it stopped decreasing for three consecutive iterations or when the 10000th iteration was reached, whichever happened first. Doing so prevents the network from updating the weights and biases beyond optima such that they give worse performance (see Yao, Rosasco, and Caponnetto, 2007, for a thorough discussion). Then, the weights and biases were considered finalized and the model is considered fitted.  
Settings for Fitting: The algorithm RMSprop, along with gradient descent and back-propagation, were used (see Shi, Li, Hong, and Sun, 2020). The settings are the suggested defaults of Keras, one of the most used NN powerhouses in the open-source world (Chollet, 2017\) and out of the scope of the current research.  
Batch Normalization: All the models additionally included batch normalization which is found to enhance performance (e.g., Chollet, 2017; Santurkar, Tsipras, Ilyas, & Mądry, 2018).   
Code and Hardware: The implementation used self-developed code available at [https://github.com/husohome/career\_ml](https://github.com/husohome/career_ml), which relies on the open source programming language Python 3.8 (Van Rossum, 1995), with Anaconda Distribution (Anaconda Software Distribution, 2020), GPU-enabled Tensforflow-gpu (Abadi, 2016\) and Keras (Chollet, 2018\) packages for the NN, and Pandas (McKinney, 2011\) and Numpy (Van Der Walt, Colbert, & Varoquaux, 2011\) for data preprocessing. The computer used was MSI Leopard GP75, with a CUDA-enabled Graphic Processing Unit (GPU) Geforce RTX 2060 which has a computation power of 6.1. The use of GPU is recommended to expedite computation (Chollet, 2017).
